/feature/atend_disparks.htm|website=www.scottware.com.au|access-date=2020-04-14|publication-date=}}</ref>\n| {{nombre|10000}} (4)\n| style=\"background-color:#ECECEC;\" | -\n| {{nombre|10000}}\n|-\n!1993<ref name=\":0\" />\n| {{nombre|9800}} (4)\n| style=\"background-color:#ECECEC;\" | -\n| {{nombre|9800}}\n|-\n!1994<ref name=\":0\" />\n| {{nombre|8800}} (5)\n| style=\"background-color:#ECECEC;\" | -\n| {{nombre|8800}}\n|-\n!1995<ref name=\":0\" />\n| {{nombre|10700}} (4)\n| style=\"background-color:#ECECEC;\" | -\n| {{nombre|10700}}\n|-\n!1996<ref name=\":0\" />\n| {{nombre|11700}} (4)\n| style=\"background-color:#ECECEC;\" | -\n| {{nombre|11700}}\n|-\n!1997<ref name=\":0\" />\n| {{nombre|12600}} (4)\n| style=\"background-color:#ECECEC;\" | -\n| {{nombre|12600}}\n|-\n!1998<ref name=\":0\" />\n| {{nombre|12500}} (4)\n| style=\"background-color:#ECECEC;\" | -\n| {{nombre|12500}}\n|-\n!1999<ref name=\":0\" />\n| {{nombre|12500}} (4)\n| style=\"background-color:#ECECEC;\" | -\n| {{nombre|12500}}\n|-\n!2000<ref name=\":0\" />\n| {{nombre|12000}} (4)\n| style=\"background-color:#ECECEC;\" | -\n| {{nombre|12000}}\n|-\n!2001<ref name=\":0\" />\n| {{nombre|12200}} (4)\n| style=\"background-color:#ECECEC;\" | -\n| {{nombre|12200}}\n|-\n!2002<ref name=\":0\" />\n| {{nombre|10300}} (5)\n| {{nombre|2800}} (>25)\n| {{nombre|13100}}\n|-\n!2003<ref name=\":0\" />\n| {{nombre|10200}} (5)\n| {{nombre|2200}} (>25)\n| {{nombre|12400}}\n|-\n!2004<ref name=\":0\" />\n| {{nombre|10200}} (5)\n| {{nombre|2200}} (>25)\n| {{nombre|12400}}\n|-\n!2005<ref name=\":0\" />\n| {{nombre|10200}} (5)\n| {{nombre|2100}} (>25)\n| {{nombre|12300}}\n|-\n! 2006<ref>{{en}} [http://www.connectingindustry.com/pdfs/TEA-ERAAttendance06.pdf 2006 TEA/ERA Attendance Report]</ref>\n| {{nombre|10600}} (5)\n| {{nombre|2200}} (>25)\n| {{nombre|12800}}\n|-\n! 2007<ref>{{cite web|title=2007 TEA/ERA Attendance Report|url=http://www.themeit.com/attendance_report2007.pdf|website=themeit.com|format=pdf|publication-date=}}</ref>\n| {{nombre|12000}} (5)\n| {{nombre|2500}} (>25)\n| {{nombre|14500}}\n|-\n! 2008<ref>{{en}} [http://www.themeit.com/TEAERA2008.pdf 2008 TEA/ERA Attendance Report]</ref>\n| {{nombre|12688}} (4)\n| {{nombre|2612}} (>25)\n| {{nombre|15300}}\n|-\n! 2009<ref>{{en}} [http://www.themeit.com/etea/2009report.pdf 2009 TEA/ERA Attendance Report]</ref> \n| {{nombre|12740}} (4)\n| {{nombre|2655}} (>25)\n| {{nombre|15395}}\n|-\n! 2010<ref>{{en}} [http://www.themeit.com/etea/2010Report.pdf 2010 TEA/ERA Attendance Report]</ref>\n| {{nombre|10500}} (6)\n| {{nombre|4500}} (19)\n| {{nombre|15000}}\n|-\n! 2011<ref>{{en}} [http://www.teaconnect.org/pdf/2011Report.pdf 2011 TEA/ERA Attendance Report]</ref> \n| {{nombre|10990}} (5)\n| {{nombre|4710}} (20)\n| {{nombre|15700}}\n|-\n! 2012<ref name=\"TEA2013\">{{en}} [http://www.iaapa.org/docs/institutes/2013-tea-aecom-study.pdf?sfvrsn=0 2013 TEA Attendance Report]</ref> \n| {{nombre|11200}} (6)\n| {{nombre|4800}} (21)\n| {{nombre|16000}}\n|-\n! 2013<ref name=\"TEA2013\"/>\n| {{nombre|10430}} (6)\n| {{nombre|4470}} (21)\n| {{nombre|14900}}\n|-\n! 2014<ref name=\"TEA2014\">{{en}} [http://www.teaconnect.org/images/files/TEA_103_49736_150603.pdf 2014 TEA Attendance Report]</ref>\n| {{nombre|9940}} (9)\n| {{nombre|4260}} (25)\n| {{nombre|14200}}\n|-\n! 2015<ref name=\"TEA2015\">{{cite web|title=2015 Theme Index & Museum Index: The Global Attractions Attendance Report|url=http://www.teaconnect.org/images/files/TEA_160_611852_160525.pdf|author=[[Themed Entertainment Association|TEA]] / [[Aecom]]|website=[[Aecom]]/TEA|pages=12<!--endif p.totales-->|language=en|format=pdf|date=2016|access-date=27 May 2016|publication-date=}}.</ref>\n| {{nombre|10360}} (9)\n| {{nombre|4440}} (>25)\n| {{nombre|14800}}\n|-\n! 2016<ref name=\"TEA2016\">{{cite web|title=2016 TEA/AECOM 2016 Theme Index & Museum Index|url=http://www.teaconnect.org/images/files/TEA_235_103719_170601.pdf|author=[[Themed Entertainment Association|TEA]] / [[Aecom]]|website=[[Aecom]]/TEA|pages=12<!--endif p.totales-->|language=en|format=pdf|date=2017|access-date=20 June 2017|publication-date=}}.</ref>\n| {{nombre|8400}} (13)\n| {{nombre|4970}} (22)\n| {{nombre|13370}}\n|-\n!2017<ref>{{cite web|title=2017 Theme Index & Museum Index: The Global Attractions Attendance Report|url=http://www.teaconnect.org/images/files/TEA_268_653730_180517.pdf|author=[[Themed Entertainment Association|TEA]] / [[Aecom]]|website=[[Aecom]]/TEA|pages=60<!--endif p.totales-->|language=en|format=pdf|date=2017|access-date=3 June 2018|publication-date=}}.</ref>\n| {{nombre|9660}} (12)\n| {{nombre|5200}} (22)\n| {{nombre|14860}}\n|-\n!2018<ref>{{cite web|title=2018 Theme Index & Museum Index: The Global Attractions Attendance Report|url=https://www.aecom.com/content/wp-content/uploads/2019/05/Theme-Index-Museum-Index-2018-2.pdf|author=[[Themed Entertainment Association|TEA]] / [[Aecom]]|website=[[Aecom]]/TEA|language=en|format=pdf|date=2018|access-date=23 May 2019|publication-date=}}.</ref>\n| {{nombre|9843}} (13)\n| {{nombre|5298}} (23)\n| {{nombre|15141}}\n|}\n=== Electroland Festival ===\nOn 8 July 2017, Disneyland hosted its first-ever EDM festival entitled Electroland, in celebration of Disneyland Paris\u2019 25th anniversary. [[Steve Aoki]], [[Nervo (DJs)|NERVO]] & [[Michael Calfan]] were the main highlights of the first edition.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://weraveyou.com/2017/07/disneyland-hosts-inaugural-edm-festival-electroland-plans-to-return-in-2018/|title=Disneyland hosts inaugural EDM festival Electroland, plans to return in 2018|date=2017-07-10|website=We Rave You|language=en-US|access-date=2019-07-15}}</ref> The second edition of the festival was held on 29 and 30 June 2018 which featured [[Afrojack]], [[Dimitri Vegas & Like Mike]], [[Klingande]], [[Robin Schulz]], [[Bob Sinclar|Bob Sinclair]], Mosimann and Lovely Laura & Ben Santiago'''.''' The third edition was held over a span of 3 days from 5 July through to 7 July in 2019. The theme of the third edition was based upon Disney's movie The Lion King. The lineup included [[Steve Aoki]] , [[Nervo (DJs)|Nervo]] , [[Showtek]] ,The Magician , [[Nicky Romero]], [[Alesso]] , [[Armin van Buuren|Armin Van Buuren]], [[Nora En Pure]] etc. Disneyland also announced the fourth edition of the 3-day festival in 2020 starting from 4 July.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://weraveyou.com/2019/07/disneyland-paris-electroland/|title=Disneyland Paris announces 4th edition of Electroland in 2020|date=2019-07-13|website=We Rave You|language=en-US|access-date=2019-07-15}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Disney|Trains|Transport|France}}\n\n*[[The Walt Disney Company]]\n*[[Rail transport in Walt Disney Parks and Resorts]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Disneyland Paris}}\n{{Wikivoyage|Disneyland Resort Paris}}\n*[http://www.disneylandparis.com/en-us/ Official website]\n\n{{Disneyland Paris}}\n{{Marne-la-Vall\u00e9e}}\n{{Disney Parks, Experiences and Products}}\n{{Disney}}\n{{Visitor attractions in Paris}}\n\n[[Category:Walt Disney Parks and Resorts|Paris]]\n[[Category:1992 establishments in France]]\n[[Category:Disneyland Paris| ]]\n[[Category:Amusement parks in France]]\n[[Category:Buildings and structures in Seine-et-Marne]]\n[[Category:Tourist attractions in \u00cele-de-France]]\n[[Category:Tourist attractions in Seine-et-Marne]]\n[[Category:Amusement parks opened in 1992]]\n", "name_user": "Dom du creu", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Disneyland_Paris"}
{"title_page": "Urbach\u2013Wiethe disease", "text_new": "{{Infobox medical condition (new)\n| name            = Urbach-Wiethe disease\n| synonyms        = '''Lipoid proteinosis''' and '''Hyalinosis cutis et mucosae'''\n| image           = Autosomal recessive - en.svg\n| caption         = Urbach\u2013Wiethe disease is inherited in an autosomal recessive manner.\n| pronounce       = \n| field           = \n| symptoms        = \n| complications   = \n| onset           = \n| duration        = \n| types           = \n| causes          = \n| risks           = \n| diagnosis       = \n| differential    = \n| prevention      = \n| treatment       = \n| medication      = \n| prognosis       = \n| frequency       = \n| deaths          = \n}}\n[[File:3767 dp sl 2.png|thumb|Urbach\u2013Wiethe disease in skin biopsy with [[H&E stain]].]]\n'''Urbach\u2013Wiethe disease'''  is a rare recessive genetic disorder, with approximately 400 reported cases since its discovery.<ref>https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/speaking-of-science/wp/2015/01/20/meet-the-woman-who-cant-feel-fear/?tid=hpModule_9d3add6c-8a79-11e2-98d9-3012c1cd8d1e&hpid=z11</ref><ref name=DiGiandomenico-etal-2006>{{cite journal | author = DiGiandomenico S, Masi R, Cassandrini D, El-Hachem M, DeVito R, Bruno C, Santorelli FM | year = 2006 | title = Lipoid proteinosis: case report and review of the literature | url = | journal = Acta Otorhinolaryngol Ital | volume = 26 | issue = | pages = 162\u20137 }}</ref><ref name=\"Andrews\">{{cite book |author1=James, William D. |author2=Berger, Timothy G. |title=Andrews' Diseases of the Skin: clinical Dermatology |publisher=Saunders Elsevier |location= |year=2006 |pages= |isbn=978-0-7216-2921-6 |oclc= |doi= |accessdate=|display-authors=etal}}</ref>  It was first officially reported in 1929 by [[Erich Urbach]] and [[Camillo Wiethe]],<ref>{{WhoNamedIt|synd|924}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal | author = Urbach E, Wiethe C | year = 1929 | title = Lipoidosis cutis et mucosae | url = | journal = Virchows Archiv f\u00fcr pathologische Anatomie und Physiologie und f\u00fcr klinische Medizin | volume = 273 | issue = | pages = 285\u2013319 }}</ref> although cases may be recognized dating back as early as 1908.<ref name=Caro-1978>{{cite journal | author = Caro I | year = 1978 | title = Lipoid proteinosis | url = | journal = International Journal of Dermatology | volume = 17 | issue = | pages = 388\u201393 }}</ref><ref name=\"isbn0-7817-3742-7\">{{cite book |author1=Lever, Walter F. |author2=Elder, David A. |title=Lever's histopathology of the skin |publisher=[[Lippincott Williams & Wilkins]] |location=Hagerstwon, MD |year=2005 |pages=440  |isbn=978-0-7817-3742-5 |oclc= |doi= |accessdate=}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal | author = Siebenmann F | year = 1908 | title = \u00dcber Mitbeteilingung der Schleimhaut bei allgemeiner Hyperkeratose der Haut | url = | journal = Arch Laryngol | volume = 20 | issue = | pages = 101\u2013109 }}</ref>\n\nThe symptoms of the disease vary greatly from individual to individual.  They may include a hoarse voice, [[lesion]]s and scarring on the skin, easily damaged skin with poor wound healing, dry, wrinkly skin, and beading of the [[papule]]s around the eyelids.<ref name=Caro-1978/><ref name=Hamada-2002-C&ED>{{Cite journal | last1 = Hamada | first1 = T. | title = Lipoid proteinosis | journal = Clinical and Experimental Dermatology | volume = 27 | issue = 8 | pages = 624\u2013629 | year = 2002 | doi = 10.1046/j.1365-2230.2002.01143.x}}</ref><ref name=Appenzeller-etal-2006-Neuroimaging16/>  All of these are results of a general thickening of the skin and [[mucous membrane]]s. In some cases there is also a hardening of brain tissue in the [[medial temporal lobe]]s, which can lead to [[epilepsy]] and neuropsychiatric abnormalities.<ref name = Staut-1998>{{Cite journal | last1 = Staut | first1 = C. C. V. | last2 = Naidich | first2 = T. P. | title = Urbach-Wiethe Disease(Lipoid Proteinosis) | journal = Pediatric Neurosurgery | volume = 28 | issue = 4 | pages = 212\u2013214 | year = 1998 | pmid = 9732251 | doi = 10.1159/000028653}}</ref>  The disease is typically not life-threatening and patients do not show a decreased [[life expectancy|life span]].<ref name=Appenzeller-etal-2006-Neuroimaging16>{{Cite journal | title = Amygdalae Calcifications Associated with Disease Duration in Lipoid Proteinosis | journal = Journal of Neuroimaging | volume = 16 | issue = 2 | pages = 154\u2013156 | year = 2006 | pmid = 16629738 | doi = 10.1111/j.1552-6569.2006.00018.x| author1 = Appenzeller | first1 = S | last2 = Chaloult | first2 = E | last3 = Velho | first3 = P | last4 = De Souza | first4 = E. M. | last5 = Ara\u00fajo | first5 = V. Z. | last6 = Cendes | first6 = F | last7 = Li | first7 = L. M. }}</ref>\n\nBecause Urbach\u2013Wiethe disease is an [[autosomal recessive]] condition, individuals can be [[genetic carrier|carriers]] of the disease but show no symptoms.   The disease is caused by loss-of-function [[mutation]]s to [[chromosome 1]] at 1q21, the extracellular matrix protein 1 ([[ECM1]]) gene.<ref name = Hamada-etal-2002>{{cite journal | author = Hamada T, McLean WHI, Ramsay M, Ashton GHS, Nanda A | display-authors = etal | year = 2002 | title = Lipoid proteinosis maps to 1q21 and is caused by mutations in the extracellular matrix protein 1 gene (ECM1) | url = | journal = Human Molecular Genetics | volume = 11 | issue = 7| pages = 833\u201340 | pmid = 11929856 }}</ref> The dermatological symptoms are caused by a buildup of a [[hyaline]] material in the dermis and the thickening of the [[basement membrane]]s in the skin.<ref name=Hamada-2002-C&ED/> Urbach\u2013Wiethe disease is typically diagnosed by its clinical dermatological manifestations, particularly the beaded papules on the eyelids.  The discovery of the mutations within the ECM1 gene has allowed the use of [[genetic testing]] to confirm an initial clinical [[diagnosis]].  [[Periodic acid-Schiff]] (PAS) and [[immunohistochemistry|immunohistochemical]] staining may also be used for diagnosis.<ref name=Caro-1978/><ref name = Chan-etal-2007>{{cite journal | author = Chan I, Liu L, Hamada T, Sethuraman G, McGrath JA | year = 2007 | title = The molecular basis of lipoid proteinosis: mutations in extracellular matrix protein 1 | url = | journal = Experimental Dermatology | volume = 16 | issue = | pages = 881\u201390 }}</ref>\n\nCurrently, there is no cure for Urbach\u2013Wiethe disease although there are ways to individually treat many of its symptoms.<ref name=DiGiandomenico-etal-2006/> The discovery of the mutations of the ECM1 gene has opened the possibility of gene therapy or a recombinant ECM1 protein for Urbach\u2013Wiethe disease treatment, but neither of these options is currently available.   Some researchers are examining patients with Urbach\u2013Wiethe disease to learn more about other conditions that exhibit similar neurological symptoms, such as [[autism]].\n\n== Symptoms ==\nUrbach\u2013Wiethe disease is characterized by both [[neurological]] and dermatological symptoms.<ref name = Siebert-etal-2003>{{cite journal | author = Siebert M, Markowitsch HJ, Bartel P | year = 2003 | title = Amygdala, affect and cognition: evidence from 10 patients with Urbach-Wiethe disease | url = | journal = Brain | volume = 126 | issue = | pages = 2627\u201337 }}</ref><ref>{{cite journal | author = Mallory SB, Krafchick BR, Holme SA, Lenane P, Krafchik BR | year = 2005 | title = What syndrome is this? Urbach-Weithe syndrome (lipoid proteinosis) | url = | journal = Pediatric Dermatology | volume = 22 | issue = | pages = 266\u20137 }}</ref>\n\n=== Dermatological ===\nAlthough [[symptom]]s can vary greatly between affected individuals, even those within the same family, symptoms normally begin in [[infancy]] and are typically a result of thickening skin and mucous membranes.<ref name=DiGiandomenico-etal-2006/>  The first symptom is often a weak cry or a hoarse voice due to a thickening of the vocal cords.  The [[hoarse]] voice can be one of the most striking clinical manifestations of the disease.<ref name=Hamada-2002-C&ED/> Lesions and scars also appear on the [[skin]], usually the [[face]] and the [[Anatomical terms of location#Proximal and distal|distal]] parts of the limbs.<ref name=Caro-1978/> This is often the result of poor wound healing and the scarring continues to increase as the patient ages, leaving the skin with a waxy appearance.  Skin may be easily damaged as a result of only a minor trauma or injury, leaving many blisters and additional scars.<ref name=Appenzeller-etal-2006-Neuroimaging16/> The skin is also usually very dry and wrinkly.  White or yellow [[Infiltration (medical)|infiltrates]] form on the lips, [[buccal mucosa]], [[tonsils]], [[uvula]], [[epiglottis]] and [[frenulum]] of the tongue.<ref name=Caro-1978/> This can lead to [[upper respiratory tract infection]] and sometimes requires [[tracheostomy]] to relieve the symptom.<ref name=Hamada-2002-C&ED/> Too much thickening of the frenulum can restrict tongue movement and may result in [[speech impediment]]s.<ref name=Thornton-etal-2008>{{cite journal | author = Thornton HB, Nel D, Thornton D, van Honk J, Baker GA, Stein DJ | year = 2008 | title = The neuropsychiatry and neuropsychology of lipoid proteinosis | url = | journal = Journal of Neuropsychiatry and Clinical Neurosciences | volume = 20 | issue = | pages = 86\u201392 }}</ref> Beading of the papules around the [[eyelid]]s is a very common symptom and is often used as part of a [[diagnosis]] of the [[disease]].  Some other [[dermatological]] symptoms that are sometimes seen but less common include [[hair loss]], [[parotitis]] and other [[Dentistry|dental]] abnormalities, [[corneal]] ulceration, and [[focal degeneration]] of the [[macula]].<ref name=Bahadir-etal-2006>{{cite journal | author = Bahadir S, Cobanoglu U, Kapicioglu Z, Kandil ST, Cimsit G | display-authors = etal | year = 2006 | title = Lipoid proteinosis: A case with ophthalmological and psychiatric findings | url = | journal = Journal of Dermatology | volume = 33 | issue = | pages = 215\u20138 }}</ref>\n\n=== Neurological ===\nAlthough the dermatological changes are the most obvious symptoms of Urbach\u2013Wiethe disease, many patients also have neurological symptoms.  About 50&ndash;75%  of the diagnosed cases of Urbach\u2013Wiethe disease also show bilateral symmetrical [[calcification]]s on the medial [[temporal lobe]]s.<ref>{{cite journal | author = Hurlemann R, Wagner M, Hawellek B, Reich H, Pieperhoff P, Amunts K | display-authors = etal | year = 2007 | title = Amygdala control of emotion-induced forgetting and remembering: Evidence from Urbach-Wiethe disease | url = | journal = Neuropsychologia | volume = 45 | issue = | pages = 877\u201384 }}</ref> These calcifications often affect the [[amygdala]] and the periamygdaloid [[gyrus|gyri]].<ref name = Staut-1998/> The amygdala is thought to be involved in processing biologically relevant stimuli and in emotional long-term memory, particularly those associated with [[fear]], and both [[Positron emission tomography|PET]] and [[Magnetic resonance imaging|MRI]] scans have shown a correlation between amygdala activation and episodic memory for strongly emotional stimuli.<ref name=Siebert-etal-2003/>  Therefore, Urbach\u2013Wiethe disease patients with calcifications and [[lesions]] in these regions may suffer impairments in these systems. These calcifications are the result of a buildup of [[calcium]] deposits in the [[blood vessel]]s within this brain region.  Over time, these vessels [[Atherosclerosis|harden]] and the tissue they are a part of dies, causing lesions.  The amount of calcification is often related to disease duration.<ref name=Appenzeller-etal-2006-Neuroimaging16/> The true prevalence of these calcifications is difficult to accurately state as not all patients undergo [[neuroimaging|brain imaging]].  Some patients also exhibit [[epilepsy]] and neuropsychiatric abnormalities. Epilepsy symptoms could begin with light anxiety attacks and can be controlled with anti-epileptic medications including Valproic Acid (Epilim).<ref name=Appenzeller-etal-2006-Neuroimaging16/>  Other patients present with symptoms similar to schizophrenia while some suffer from mood, [[anxiety]], and psychotic disorders.<ref name = Thornton-etal-2008/><ref name = Cinaz-1993>{{cite journal | author = Cinaz P, Guvenir T, Gonlusen G | year = 1993 | title = Lipoid proteinosis: Urbach-Wiethe disease | url = | journal = Acta Paediatrica | volume = 82 | issue = | pages = 892\u20133 }}</ref> [[File:Chromosome 1.svg|frame|Chromosome 1, where the ECM1 mutation occurs at 1[[Centromere#Centromere positions|q]]21]]\n\n== Causes ==\nResearchers have mapped Urbach\u2013Wiethe disease to [[chromosome 1]] at 1q21 and specifically identified the extracellular matrix protein 1 ([[ECM1]]) gene as the gene containing mutations that can lead to the development of the condition.<ref name = Hamada-etal-2002/> At this point, 41 different mutations within ECM1 have been reported to lead to Urbach\u2013Wiethe disease.<ref name = Chan-etal-2007/> These were all [[zygosity|homozygous]] loss-of-function mutations (i.e. [[Nonsense mutation|nonsense]], [[Frameshift mutation|frameshift]] or internal [[Deletion mutation|deletions]]).<ref name=Hamada-2002-C&ED/> It is an [[autosomal recessive]] condition,<ref name=DiGiandomenico-etal-2006/><ref name=Chan-etal-2007/> requiring two mutated copies of the ECM1 gene to cause the disease.\n\nECM1 codes for a [[glycoprotein]] of previously unknown origin.  The discovery that the loss of ECM1 expression leads to the symptoms associated with Urbach\u2013Wiethe disease suggests that ECM1 may contribute to skin adhesion, epidermal differentiation, and wound healing and scarring.<ref name=Hamada-etal-2002/>  It is also thought to play a role in endochondral bone formation, tumor biology, endothelial cell proliferation and blood vessel formation.<ref name=Hamada-2002-C&ED/>\n\nThe dermatological symptoms are caused by a buildup of a [[hyaline]] material in the dermis and the thickening of the basement membranes in the skin.<ref name=Hamada-2002-C&ED/> The nature of this material is unknown, but researchers have suggested that it may be a glycoprotein, a [[glycolipid]], an acid [[mucopolysaccharide]], altered [[collagen]] or elastic tissue.<ref name=Caro-1978/>\n\n== Diagnosis ==\nUrbach\u2013Wiethe disease is typically diagnosed by its clinical dermatological manifestations, particularly the beaded papules on the eyelids.  Doctors can also test the hyaline material with a periodic acid-Schiff (PAS) staining, as the material colors strongly for this stain.<ref name=Caro-1978/>\n\nImmunohistochemical skin labeling for [[antibody|antibodies]] for the ECM1 protein as labeling has been shown to be reduced in the skin of those affected by Urbach\u2013Wiethe disease.<ref name = Chan-etal-2007/>  Staining with anti-type IV collagen antibodies or anti-type VII collagen antibodies reveals bright, thick bands at the [[dermoepidermal junction]].<ref name=Hamada-2002-C&ED/>\n\nNon-contrast [[computed tomography|CT scans]] can image calcifications, but this is not typically used as a means of diagnosing the disease.  This is partly due to the fact that not all Urbach-Wiethe patients exhibit calcifications, but also because similar lesions can be formed from other diseases such as [[herpes simplex]] and [[encephalitis]].  The discovery of mutations within the ECM1 gene has allowed the use of genetic testing to confirm initial clinical diagnoses of Urbach\u2013Wiethe disease.  It also allows doctors to better distinguish between Urbach\u2013Wiethe disease and other similar diseases not caused by mutations in ECM1.\n\n== Treatment ==\nCurrently, there is no cure for Urbach\u2013Wiethe disease although there are some ways to individually treat many of its symptoms.  There has been some success with oral [[dimethyl sulfoxide]] (DMSO) and intralesional [[heparin]], but this is not true in all cases.<ref name=Hamada-2002-C&ED/><ref name = Cinaz-1993/> D-[[penicillamine]] has also shown promise, but has yet to have been used extensively.<ref name = Chan-etal-2007/>  There are also some reports of patients being treated with [[etretinate]], a drug typically prescribed to treat [[psoriasis]].<ref name=Bahadir-etal-2006/> In some cases, calcifications in the brain can lead to abnormal electrical activity among neurons.  Some patients are given anti-seizure medication to help deal with these abnormalities.  [[Tracheostomy]] is often used to relieve upper respiratory tract infections. [[Carbon dioxide]] laser surgery of thickened [[vocal folds|vocal cords]] and beaded eyelid papules have improved these symptoms for patients.<ref name=Hamada-2002-C&ED/>  The discovery of the mutations of the ECM1 gene has opened the possibility of gene therapy or a [[Recombinant DNA|recombinant]] EMC1 protein for Urbach\u2013Wiethe disease treatment, but neither of these two options are currently available.\n\n== Prognosis ==\nUrbach\u2013Wiethe disease is typically not a life-threatening condition.<ref name=DiGiandomenico-etal-2006/> The life expectancy of these patients is normal as long as the potential side effects of thickening mucosa, such as respiratory obstruction, are properly addressed.<ref name=Appenzeller-etal-2006-Neuroimaging16/> Although this may require a tracheostomy or carbon dioxide laser surgery, such steps can help ensure that individuals with Urbach\u2013Wiethe disease are able to live a full life.  Oral [[dimethyl sulfoxide]]&nbsp;(DMSO) has been shown to reduce skin lesions, helping to minimize discomfort for these individuals.<ref name=Hamada-2002-C&ED/>\n\n== Incidence ==\nUrbach\u2013Wiethe disease is very rare; there are fewer than 300 reported cases in [[medical literature]].<ref name=DiGiandomenico-etal-2006/> Although Urbach\u2013Wiethe disease can be found worldwide, almost a quarter of reported diagnoses are in [[South Africa]].<ref name=DiGiandomenico-etal-2006/> Many of these are in patients of [[Dutch people|Dutch]], [[German people|German]], and [[Khoisan]] ancestry.<ref name=DiGiandomenico-etal-2006/><ref name=Hamada-etal-2002/> This high frequency is thought to be due to the [[founder effect]].<ref name = Chan-etal-2007/> Due to its recessive genetic cause and the ability to be a carrier of the disease without symptoms, Urbach\u2013Wiethe disease often runs in families.  In some regions of South Africa, up to one in 12 individuals may be carriers of the disease.<ref name=Hamada-2002-C&ED/>  Most of the case studies involving Urbach\u2013Wiethe disease patients involve only one to three cases and these cases are often in the same family.  Due to its low incidence, it is difficult to find a large enough number of cases to adequately study the disease.\n\n== History ==\nIn 1908, what appears to be the first case of Urbach\u2013Wiethe disease was reported by [[Friedrich Siebenmann]], a professor of [[otolaryngology]] in [[Basel]], [[Switzerland]].  In 1925, [[Friedrich Miescher]], a Swiss dermatologist, reported on three similar patients.<ref name=Caro-1978/> An official report of Urbach\u2013Wiethe disease was first described in 1929 by a Viennese dermatologist and otorhinolaryngologist, Urbach and Wiethe.<ref name = Hamada-etal-2002/> Its original name of 'lipoidosis cutis et mucosae' was changed to 'lipoid proteinosis cutis et mucosae' due to Urbach's belief that the condition was due to abnormal [[lipid]] and [[protein]] deposits within the tissues.<ref name = Hamada-etal-2002/> Some have debated as to whether or not the disease is actually a form of [[mucopolysaccharidosis]], [[amyloidosis]], or even [[porphyria]].  The discovery of the Urbach\u2013Wiethe disease causing mutation to the ECM1 gene has now provided a definitive way to differentiate Urbach\u2013Wiethe disease from these other conditions.<ref name=Hamada-2002-C&ED/>\n\n== Society ==\nUrbach\u2013Wiethe disease is used as the main plot element in a 2013 Dutch novel, ''De angstjager'' (The Fear Hunter) by author [[Joris van Os]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.uitgeverijdebrouwerij.nl/de-angstjager/|title=De Angstjager|first=Bravebox|last=www.bravebox.nl|date=|website=uitgeverijdebrouwerij.nl|access-date=30 April 2019}}</ref>\n\nReleased in 2015, ''A Fearless Life'' by author Joshua McCloskey is about a young woman's life living with Urbach-Wiethe.<ref>{{Cite book|title = A Fearless Life|asin = B015ONZQ2Y|publisher = Joshua McCloskey|date = 2015-09-21|language = English|first = Joshua|last = McCloskey}}</ref>\n\nUrbach\u2013Wiethe disease and the case study of SM-046 are the source of the main plot elements in two stories in ''Movemind'' by author Robert New.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://robertsnew.com/2018/06/25/whats-my-favourite-piece-of-my-writing/|title=What's my favourite piece of my writing?|author=|date=26 June 2018|website=robertsnew.com|access-date=30 April 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|title = Movemind|asin = B07BQ9K92J|publisher = Tale Publishing|date = 2018-06-01|language = English|first = Robert|last = New}}</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n* [[S.M. (patient)]]\n* [[List of cutaneous conditions]]\n* [[List of radiographic findings associated with cutaneous conditions]]\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Medical resources\n| DiseasesDB      = 30808\n| ICD10           = {{ICD10|E|78|8|e|70}}\n| ICD9            = {{ICD9|272.8}}\n| ICDO            = \n| OMIM            = 247100\n| MedlinePlus     = \n| eMedicineSubj   = derm\n| eMedicineTopic  = 241\n| MeshID          = D008065\n| SNOMED CT       = 38692000\n}}\n\n{{Scleroprotein disease}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Urbach-Wiethe Disease}}\n[[Category:Lipid metabolism disorders]]\n[[Category:Autosomal recessive disorders]]\n[[Category:Skin conditions resulting from errors in metabolism]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox medical condition (new)\n| name            = Urbach-Wiethe disease\n| synonyms        = '''Lipoid proteinosis''' and '''Hyalinosis cutis et mucosae'''\n| image           = Autosomal recessive - en.svg\n| caption         = Urbach\u2013Wiethe disease is inherited in an autosomal recessive manner.\n| pronounce       = \n| field           = \n| symptoms        = \n| complications   = \n| onset           = \n| duration        = \n| types           = \n| causes          = \n| risks           = \n| diagnosis       = \n| differential    = \n| prevention      = \n| treatment       = \n| medication      = \n| prognosis       = \n| frequency       = \n| deaths          = \n}}\n[[File:3767 dp sl 2.png|thumb|Urbach\u2013Wiethe disease in skin biopsy with [[H&E stain]].]]\n'''Urbach\u2013Wiethe disease'''  is a rare recessive genetic disorder, with approximately 400 reported cases since its discovery.<ref>https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/speaking-of-science/wp/2015/01/20/meet-the-woman-who-cant-feel-fear/?tid=hpModule_9d3add6c-8a79-11e2-98d9-3012c1cd8d1e&hpid=z11</ref><ref name=DiGiandomenico-etal-2006>DiGiandomenico S, Masi R, Cassandrini D, El-Hachem M, DeVito R, Bruno C, Santorelli FM. 2006. Lipoid proteinosis: case report and review of the literature. ''Acta Otorhinolaryngol Ital'' 26:162&ndash;7</ref><ref name=\"Andrews\">{{cite book |author1=James, William D. |author2=Berger, Timothy G. |title=Andrews' Diseases of the Skin: clinical Dermatology |publisher=Saunders Elsevier |location= |year=2006 |pages= |isbn=978-0-7216-2921-6 |oclc= |doi= |accessdate=|display-authors=etal}}</ref>  It was first officially reported in 1929 by [[Erich Urbach]] and [[Camillo Wiethe]],<ref>{{WhoNamedIt|synd|924}}</ref><ref>Urbach E, Wiethe C. 1929. Lipoidosis cutis et mucosae. ''Virchows Archiv f\u00fcr pathologische Anatomie und Physiologie und f\u00fcr klinische Medizin'' 273: 285&ndash;319</ref> although cases may be recognized dating back as early as 1908.<ref name=Caro-1978>Caro I. 1978. Lipoid proteinosis. ''International Journal of Dermatology''. 17:388&ndash;93</ref><ref name=\"isbn0-7817-3742-7\">{{cite book |author1=Lever, Walter F. |author2=Elder, David A. |title=Lever's histopathology of the skin |publisher=[[Lippincott Williams & Wilkins]] |location=Hagerstwon, MD |year=2005 |pages=440  |isbn=978-0-7817-3742-5 |oclc= |doi= |accessdate=}}</ref><ref>Siebenmann F. 1908. \u00dcber Mitbeteilingung der Schleimhaut bei allgemeiner Hyperkeratose der Haut. ''Arch Laryngol'' 20:101&ndash;109</ref>\n\nThe symptoms of the disease vary greatly from individual to individual.  They may include a hoarse voice, [[lesion]]s and scarring on the skin, easily damaged skin with poor wound healing, dry, wrinkly skin, and beading of the [[papule]]s around the eyelids.<ref name=Caro-1978/><ref name=Hamada-2002-C&ED>{{Cite journal | last1 = Hamada | first1 = T. | title = Lipoid proteinosis | journal = Clinical and Experimental Dermatology | volume = 27 | issue = 8 | pages = 624\u2013629 | year = 2002 | doi = 10.1046/j.1365-2230.2002.01143.x}}</ref><ref name=Appenzeller-etal-2006-Neuroimaging16/>  All of these are results of a general thickening of the skin and [[mucous membrane]]s. In some cases there is also a hardening of brain tissue in the [[medial temporal lobe]]s, which can lead to [[epilepsy]] and neuropsychiatric abnormalities.<ref name = Staut-1998>{{Cite journal | last1 = Staut | first1 = C. C. V. | last2 = Naidich | first2 = T. P. | title = Urbach-Wiethe Disease(Lipoid Proteinosis) | journal = Pediatric Neurosurgery | volume = 28 | issue = 4 | pages = 212\u2013214 | year = 1998 | pmid = 9732251 | doi = 10.1159/000028653}}</ref>  The disease is typically not life-threatening and patients do not show a decreased [[life expectancy|life span]].<ref name=Appenzeller-etal-2006-Neuroimaging16>{{Cite journal | title = Amygdalae Calcifications Associated with Disease Duration in Lipoid Proteinosis | journal = Journal of Neuroimaging | volume = 16 | issue = 2 | pages = 154\u2013156 | year = 2006 | pmid = 16629738 | doi = 10.1111/j.1552-6569.2006.00018.x| author1 = Appenzeller | first1 = S | last2 = Chaloult | first2 = E | last3 = Velho | first3 = P | last4 = De Souza | first4 = E. M. | last5 = Ara\u00fajo | first5 = V. Z. | last6 = Cendes | first6 = F | last7 = Li | first7 = L. M. }}</ref>\n\nBecause Urbach\u2013Wiethe disease is an [[autosomal recessive]] condition, individuals can be [[genetic carrier|carriers]] of the disease but show no symptoms.   The disease is caused by loss-of-function [[mutation]]s to [[chromosome 1]] at 1q21, the extracellular matrix protein 1 ([[ECM1]]) gene.<ref name = Hamada-etal-2002>Hamada T, McLean WHI, Ramsay M, Ashton GHS, Nanda A, et al. 2002. Lipoid proteinosis maps to 1q21 and is caused by mutations in the extracellular matrix protein 1 gene (ECM1). ''Human Molecular Genetics'' 11:833&ndash;40 {{PMID|11929856}}</ref> The dermatological symptoms are caused by a buildup of a [[hyaline]] material in the dermis and the thickening of the [[basement membrane]]s in the skin.<ref name=Hamada-2002-C&ED/> Urbach\u2013Wiethe disease is typically diagnosed by its clinical dermatological manifestations, particularly the beaded papules on the eyelids.  The discovery of the mutations within the ECM1 gene has allowed the use of [[genetic testing]] to confirm an initial clinical [[diagnosis]].  [[Periodic acid-Schiff]] (PAS) and [[immunohistochemistry|immunohistochemical]] staining may also be used for diagnosis.<ref name=Caro-1978/><ref name = Chan-etal-2007>Chan I, Liu L, Hamada T, Sethuraman G, McGrath JA. 2007. The molecular basis of lipoid proteinosis: mutations in extracellular matrix protein 1. ''Experimental Dermatology'' 16:881&ndash;90</ref>\n\nCurrently, there is no cure for Urbach\u2013Wiethe disease although there are ways to individually treat many of its symptoms.<ref name=DiGiandomenico-etal-2006/> The discovery of the mutations of the ECM1 gene has opened the possibility of gene therapy or a recombinant ECM1 protein for Urbach\u2013Wiethe disease treatment, but neither of these options is currently available.   Some researchers are examining patients with Urbach\u2013Wiethe disease to learn more about other conditions that exhibit similar neurological symptoms, such as [[autism]].\n\n== Symptoms ==\nUrbach\u2013Wiethe disease is characterized by both [[neurological]] and dermatological symptoms.<ref name = Siebert-etal-2003>Siebert M, [[Hans Markowitsch|Markowitsch HJ]], Bartel P. 2003. Amygdala, affect and cognition: evidence from 10 patients with Urbach-Wiethe disease. ''Brain'' 126:2627&ndash;37</ref><ref>Mallory SB, Krafchick BR, Holme SA, Lenane P, Krafchik BR. 2005. What syndrome is this? Urbach-Weithe syndrome (lipoid proteinosis). ''Pediatric Dermatology'' 22:266&ndash;7</ref>\n\n=== Dermatological ===\nAlthough [[symptom]]s can vary greatly between affected individuals, even those within the same family, symptoms normally begin in [[infancy]] and are typically a result of thickening skin and mucous membranes.<ref name=DiGiandomenico-etal-2006/>  The first symptom is often a weak cry or a hoarse voice due to a thickening of the vocal cords.  The [[hoarse]] voice can be one of the most striking clinical manifestations of the disease.<ref name=Hamada-2002-C&ED/> Lesions and scars also appear on the [[skin]], usually the [[face]] and the [[Anatomical terms of location#Proximal and distal|distal]] parts of the limbs.<ref name=Caro-1978/> This is often the result of poor wound healing and the scarring continues to increase as the patient ages, leaving the skin with a waxy appearance.  Skin may be easily damaged as a result of only a minor trauma or injury, leaving many blisters and additional scars.<ref name=Appenzeller-etal-2006-Neuroimaging16/> The skin is also usually very dry and wrinkly.  White or yellow [[Infiltration (medical)|infiltrates]] form on the lips, [[buccal mucosa]], [[tonsils]], [[uvula]], [[epiglottis]] and [[frenulum]] of the tongue.<ref name=Caro-1978/> This can lead to [[upper respiratory tract infection]] and sometimes requires [[tracheostomy]] to relieve the symptom.<ref name=Hamada-2002-C&ED/> Too much thickening of the frenulum can restrict tongue movement and may result in [[speech impediment]]s.<ref name=Thornton-etal-2008>Thornton HB, Nel D, Thornton D, van Honk J, Baker GA, Stein DJ. 2008. The neuropsychiatry and neuropsychology of lipoid proteinosis. ''Journal of Neuropsychiatry and Clinical Neurosciences'' 20:86&ndash;92</ref> Beading of the papules around the [[eyelid]]s is a very common symptom and is often used as part of a [[diagnosis]] of the [[disease]].  Some other [[dermatological]] symptoms that are sometimes seen but less common include [[hair loss]], [[parotitis]] and other [[Dentistry|dental]] abnormalities, [[corneal]] ulceration, and [[focal degeneration]] of the [[macula]].<ref name=Bahadir-etal-2006>Bahadir S, Cobanoglu U, Kapicioglu Z, Kandil ST, Cimsit G, et al. 2006. Lipoid proteinosis: A case with ophthalmological and psychiatric findings. ''Journal of Dermatology'' 33:215&ndash;8</ref>\n\n=== Neurological ===\nAlthough the dermatological changes are the most obvious symptoms of Urbach\u2013Wiethe disease, many patients also have neurological symptoms.  About 50&ndash;75%  of the diagnosed cases of Urbach\u2013Wiethe disease also show bilateral symmetrical [[calcification]]s on the medial [[temporal lobe]]s.<ref>Hurlemann R, Wagner M, Hawellek B, Reich H, Pieperhoff P, Amunts K, et al. 2007. Amygdala control of emotion-induced forgetting and remembering: Evidence from Urbach-Wiethe disease. ''Neuropsychologia'' 45:877&ndash;84</ref> These calcifications often affect the [[amygdala]] and the periamygdaloid [[gyrus|gyri]].<ref name = Staut-1998/> The amygdala is thought to be involved in processing biologically relevant stimuli and in emotional long-term memory, particularly those associated with [[fear]], and both [[Positron emission tomography|PET]] and [[Magnetic resonance imaging|MRI]] scans have shown a correlation between amygdala activation and episodic memory for strongly emotional stimuli.<ref name=Siebert-etal-2003/>  Therefore, Urbach\u2013Wiethe disease patients with calcifications and [[lesions]] in these regions may suffer impairments in these systems. These calcifications are the result of a buildup of [[calcium]] deposits in the [[blood vessel]]s within this brain region.  Over time, these vessels [[Atherosclerosis|harden]] and the tissue they are a part of dies, causing lesions.  The amount of calcification is often related to disease duration.<ref name=Appenzeller-etal-2006-Neuroimaging16/> The true prevalence of these calcifications is difficult to accurately state as not all patients undergo [[neuroimaging|brain imaging]].  Some patients also exhibit [[epilepsy]] and neuropsychiatric abnormalities. Epilepsy symptoms could begin with light anxiety attacks and can be controlled with anti-epileptic medications including Valproic Acid (Epilim). <ref name=Appenzeller-etal-2006-Neuroimaging16/>  Other patients present with symptoms similar to schizophrenia while some suffer from mood, [[anxiety]], and psychotic disorders.<ref name = Thornton-etal-2008/><ref name = Cinaz-1993>Cinaz P, Guvenir T, Gonlusen G. 1993. Lipoid proteinosis: Urbach-Wiethe disease. ''Acta Paediatrica'' 82:892&ndash;3</ref> [[File:Chromosome 1.svg|frame|Chromosome 1, where the ECM1 mutation occurs at 1[[Centromere#Centromere positions|q]]21]]\n\n== Causes ==\nResearchers have mapped Urbach\u2013Wiethe disease to [[chromosome 1]] at 1q21 and specifically identified the extracellular matrix protein 1 ([[ECM1]]) gene as the gene containing mutations that can lead to the development of the condition.<ref name = Hamada-etal-2002/> At this point, 41 different mutations within ECM1 have been reported to lead to Urbach\u2013Wiethe disease.<ref name = Chan-etal-2007/> These were all [[zygosity|homozygous]] loss-of-function mutations (i.e. [[Nonsense mutation|nonsense]], [[Frameshift mutation|frameshift]] or internal [[Deletion mutation|deletions]]).<ref name=Hamada-2002-C&ED/> It is an [[autosomal recessive]] condition,<ref name=DiGiandomenico-etal-2006/><ref name=Chan-etal-2007/> requiring two mutated copies of the ECM1 gene to cause the disease.\n\nECM1 codes for a [[glycoprotein]] of previously unknown origin.  The discovery that the loss of ECM1 expression leads to the symptoms associated with Urbach\u2013Wiethe disease suggests that ECM1 may contribute to skin adhesion, epidermal differentiation, and wound healing and scarring.<ref name=Hamada-etal-2002/>  It is also thought to play a role in endochondral bone formation, tumor biology, endothelial cell proliferation and blood vessel formation.<ref name=Hamada-2002-C&ED/>\n\nThe dermatological symptoms are caused by a buildup of a [[hyaline]] material in the dermis and the thickening of the basement membranes in the skin.<ref name=Hamada-2002-C&ED/> The nature of this material is unknown, but researchers have suggested that it may be a glycoprotein, a [[glycolipid]], an acid [[mucopolysaccharide]], altered [[collagen]] or elastic tissue.<ref name=Caro-1978/>\n\n== Diagnosis ==\nUrbach\u2013Wiethe disease is typically diagnosed by its clinical dermatological manifestations, particularly the beaded papules on the eyelids.  Doctors can also test the hyaline material with a periodic acid-Schiff (PAS) staining, as the material colors strongly for this stain.<ref name=Caro-1978/>\n\nImmunohistochemical skin labeling for [[antibody|antibodies]] for the ECM1 protein as labeling has been shown to be reduced in the skin of those affected by Urbach\u2013Wiethe disease.<ref name = Chan-etal-2007/>  Staining with anti-type IV collagen antibodies or anti-type VII collagen antibodies reveals bright, thick bands at the [[dermoepidermal junction]].<ref name=Hamada-2002-C&ED/>\n\nNon-contrast [[computed tomography|CT scans]] can image calcifications, but this is not typically used as a means of diagnosing the disease.  This is partly due to the fact that not all Urbach-Wiethe patients exhibit calcifications, but also because similar lesions can be formed from other diseases such as [[herpes simplex]] and [[encephalitis]].  The discovery of mutations within the ECM1 gene has allowed the use of genetic testing to confirm initial clinical diagnoses of Urbach\u2013Wiethe disease.  It also allows doctors to better distinguish between Urbach\u2013Wiethe disease and other similar diseases not caused by mutations in ECM1.\n\n== Treatment ==\nCurrently, there is no cure for Urbach\u2013Wiethe disease although there are some ways to individually treat many of its symptoms.  There has been some success with oral [[dimethyl sulfoxide]] (DMSO) and intralesional [[heparin]], but this is not true in all cases.<ref name=Hamada-2002-C&ED/><ref name = Cinaz-1993/> D-[[penicillamine]] has also shown promise, but has yet to have been used extensively.<ref name = Chan-etal-2007/>  There are also some reports of patients being treated with [[etretinate]], a drug typically prescribed to treat [[psoriasis]].<ref name=Bahadir-etal-2006/> In some cases, calcifications in the brain can lead to abnormal electrical activity among neurons.  Some patients are given anti-seizure medication to help deal with these abnormalities.  [[Tracheostomy]] is often used to relieve upper respiratory tract infections. [[Carbon dioxide]] laser surgery of thickened [[vocal folds|vocal cords]] and beaded eyelid papules have improved these symptoms for patients.<ref name=Hamada-2002-C&ED/>  The discovery of the mutations of the ECM1 gene has opened the possibility of gene therapy or a [[Recombinant DNA|recombinant]] EMC1 protein for Urbach\u2013Wiethe disease treatment, but neither of these two options are currently available.\n\n== Prognosis ==\nUrbach\u2013Wiethe disease is typically not a life-threatening condition.<ref name=DiGiandomenico-etal-2006/> The life expectancy of these patients is normal as long as the potential side effects of thickening mucosa, such as respiratory obstruction, are properly addressed.<ref name=Appenzeller-etal-2006-Neuroimaging16/> Although this may require a tracheostomy or carbon dioxide laser surgery, such steps can help ensure that individuals with Urbach\u2013Wiethe disease are able to live a full life.  Oral [[dimethyl sulfoxide]]&nbsp;(DMSO) has been shown to reduce skin lesions, helping to minimize discomfort for these individuals.<ref name=Hamada-2002-C&ED/>\n\n== Incidence ==\nUrbach\u2013Wiethe disease is very rare; there are fewer than 300 reported cases in [[medical literature]].<ref name=DiGiandomenico-etal-2006/> Although Urbach\u2013Wiethe disease can be found worldwide, almost a quarter of reported diagnoses are in [[South Africa]].<ref name=DiGiandomenico-etal-2006/> Many of these are in patients of [[Dutch people|Dutch]], [[German people|German]], and [[Khoisan]] ancestry.<ref name=DiGiandomenico-etal-2006/><ref name=Hamada-etal-2002/> This high frequency is thought to be due to the [[founder effect]].<ref name = Chan-etal-2007/> Due to its recessive genetic cause and the ability to be a carrier of the disease without symptoms, Urbach\u2013Wiethe disease often runs in families.  In some regions of South Africa, up to one in 12 individuals may be carriers of the disease.<ref name=Hamada-2002-C&ED/>  Most of the case studies involving Urbach\u2013Wiethe disease patients involve only one to three cases and these cases are often in the same family.  Due to its low incidence, it is difficult to find a large enough number of cases to adequately study the disease.\n\n== History ==\nIn 1908, what appears to be the first case of Urbach\u2013Wiethe disease was reported by [[Friedrich Siebenmann]], a professor of [[otolaryngology]] in [[Basel]], [[Switzerland]].  In 1925, [[Friedrich Miescher]], a Swiss dermatologist, reported on three similar patients.<ref name=Caro-1978/> An official report of Urbach\u2013Wiethe disease was first described in 1929 by a Viennese dermatologist and otorhinolaryngologist, Urbach and Wiethe.<ref name = Hamada-etal-2002/> Its original name of 'lipoidosis cutis et mucosae' was changed to 'lipoid proteinosis cutis et mucosae' due to Urbach's belief that the condition was due to abnormal [[lipid]] and [[protein]] deposits within the tissues.<ref name = Hamada-etal-2002/> Some have debated as to whether or not the disease is actually a form of [[mucopolysaccharidosis]], [[amyloidosis]], or even [[porphyria]].  The discovery of the Urbach\u2013Wiethe disease causing mutation to the ECM1 gene has now provided a definitive way to differentiate Urbach\u2013Wiethe disease from these other conditions.<ref name=Hamada-2002-C&ED/>\n\n== Society ==\nUrbach\u2013Wiethe disease is used as the main plot element in a 2013 Dutch novel, ''De angstjager'' (The Fear Hunter) by author [[Joris van Os]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.uitgeverijdebrouwerij.nl/de-angstjager/|title=De Angstjager|first=Bravebox|last=www.bravebox.nl|date=|website=uitgeverijdebrouwerij.nl|access-date=30 April 2019}}</ref>\n\nReleased in 2015, ''A Fearless Life'' by author Joshua McCloskey is about a young woman's life living with Urbach-Wiethe.<ref>{{Cite book|title = A Fearless Life|asin = B015ONZQ2Y|publisher = Joshua McCloskey|date = 2015-09-21|language = English|first = Joshua|last = McCloskey}}</ref>\n\nUrbach-Wiethe disease and the case study of SM-046 are the source of the main plot elements in two stories in ''Movemind'' by author Robert New. <ref>{{cite web|url=https://robertsnew.com/2018/06/25/whats-my-favourite-piece-of-my-writing/|title=What's my favourite piece of my writing?|author=|date=26 June 2018|website=robertsnew.com|access-date=30 April 2019}}</ref> <ref>{{Cite book|title = Movemind|asin = B07BQ9K92J|publisher = Tale Publishing|date = 2018-06-01|language = English|first = Robert|last = New}}</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n* [[S.M. (patient)]]\n* [[List of cutaneous conditions]]\n* [[List of radiographic findings associated with cutaneous conditions]]\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Medical resources\n| DiseasesDB      = 30808\n| ICD10           = {{ICD10|E|78|8|e|70}}\n| ICD9            = {{ICD9|272.8}}\n| ICDO            = \n| OMIM            = 247100\n| MedlinePlus     = \n| eMedicineSubj   = derm\n| eMedicineTopic  = 241\n| MeshID          = D008065\n| SNOMED CT       = 38692000\n}}\n\n\n{{Scleroprotein disease}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Urbach-Wiethe Disease}}\n[[Category:Lipid metabolism disorders]]\n[[Category:Autosomal recessive disorders]]\n[[Category:Skin conditions resulting from errors in metabolism]]\n", "name_user": "Rjwilmsi", "label": "safe", "comment": "Journal cites:, templated 12 journal cites, added 1 issue number", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Urbach%E2%80%93Wiethe_disease"}
{"title_page": "Praveen Linga", "text_new": "{{short description|Chemical engineering professor (b. 1979)}}\n{{Autobiography|date=March 2020}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name          = Praveen Linga\n| image         = Prof Linga in his lab.jpg\n| image_size    = \n| caption       = Linga in his lab at NUS\n| birth_name    = \n| birth_date    = \n| birth_place   = [[India]]\n| death_date    = \n| death_place   = \n| death_cause   = \n| resting_place = \n| resting_place_coordinates = \n| residence     = [[Singapore]]\n| nationality   = \n| other_names   = \n| known_for     = \n| education     = [[University of Madras]] <br> [[Indian Institute of Technology Kharagpur]]<br>[[The University of British Columbia]]\n| employer      = [[National University of Singapore]] [[Singapore]]\n| occupation    = Academic\n| title         = Dean's Chair Associate Professor at the Department of Chemical and Biomolecular Engineering\n| boards        = \n| spouse        = \n| partner       = \n| children      = \n| parents       = \n| relatives     = \n| signature     = \n| website       = {{url|gashydrates.chbe.nus.edu.sg}}\n| footnotes     = \n}}\n\n'''Praveen Linga''' is a professor at the [[National University of Singapore]]'s Department of Chemical and Biomolecular Engineering. He is also the co-founder of NewGen Gas Pte Ltd<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://newgengas.com/index.php/our-technology-4|title=About Us|website=newgengas.com}}</ref>, a spin-off company that specializes in solidified natural gas (SNG) technology via [[clathrate hydrates]] for natural gas storage and transport.\n\n==Educational background==\nLinga was born on April 21, 1979 in Chennai, India. His father was an agriculturist. During his primary years of education, up to 3rd standard, he went to [[St. Mary's Home Matriculation School]] in Kothagiri, Tamil Nadu, India. From 6th to 12th standard, he studied at Infant Jesus Matriculation Higher Secondary School in Manali New Town, Chennai, India. He obtained his Bachelor of Technology degree in Chemical Engineering from Sri Ram Engineering College affiliated to the [[University of Madras]] in 2000. He then went on to pursue his Master of Technology degree at [[Indian Institute of Technology Kharagpur]] and graduated in 2002.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://kgpchronicle.iitkgp.ac.in/frsc-for-kgpian-praveen-linga/|title=FRSC for Kgpian Praveen Linga \u2013 The KGP Chronicle}}</ref> In 2004, he joined the Department of Chemical and Biological Engineering at [[The University of British Columbia]] to pursue his doctoral studies. Under the supervision of Professor Peter Englezos, he obtained his doctoral degree in 2009.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.grad.ubc.ca/prospective-students/graduate-student-research/convocation-may-2009|title=Convocation May 2009|website=UBC Graduate and Postdoctoral Studies}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://academictree.org/etree/tree.php?pid=100963|title=E-Tree - Praveen Linga Family Tree|website=academictree.org}}</ref> He did his Postdoctoral fellowship in the Department of Chemical and Biological Engineering at [[The University of British Columbia]] for a year (2009-2010). He was the first in his family's lineage to pursue post graduation in education.\n\n==Career==\n\nIn 2010, he started his academic career at the National University of Singapore (NUS) as an Assistant Professor in the Department of Chemical and Biomolecular Engineering specializing in gas hydrates technology. In 2016, he was appointed as an Associate Professor with tenure and in 2019, he was appointed as the Dean's Chair Associate Professor.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.eng.nus.edu.sg/chbe/staff/chepl/ |title=Staff |publisher=www.eng.nus.edu.sg |date= |accessdate=2020-02-14}}</ref>\nHe is also a visiting professor of Guangzhou Institute of Energy Conversion<ref>{{cite web|url=http://gashydrates.chbe.nus.edu.sg/Achievements/2018-2022_GIEC-CAS%20Institute%20Approval.jpeg |title=Instsute approval |publisher=gashydrates.chbe.nus.edu.sg |date=2018 |accessdate=2020-02-14}}</ref> Chinese Academy of Sciences, Guangzhou, [[PR China]] and a visiting guest professor of [[Harbin Engineering University]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://gashydrates.chbe.nus.edu.sg/Achievements/Harbin%20Engineering%20University_Visiting%20Professor%20Appointment.jpeg |title=Visiting professors |publisher=gashydrates.chbe.nus.edu.sg |date= |accessdate=2020-02-14}}</ref> [[PR China]].\n\nHe is a licensed Professional Engineer (P.Eng.) in Singapore. He also serves as a scientific editor in various engineering journals \n* Subject Editor: [[Applied Energy]] (Elsevier)<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.journals.elsevier.com/applied-energy/editorial-board|title=Applied Energy Editorial Board|via=www.journals.elsevier.com}}</ref>\n* Associate Editor: Journal of Natural Gas Science and Engineering (Elsevier)<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.journals.elsevier.com/journal-of-natural-gas-science-and-engineering/editorial-board|title=Journal of Natural Gas Science and Engineering Editorial Board|via=www.journals.elsevier.com}}</ref>\n* Editorial Advisory Board Member: [[Energy & Fuels]] (ACS Publisher)<ref>{{cite journal|url=https://pubs.acs.org/journal/enfuem|title=Energy & Fuels|website=pubs.acs.org|doi=10.1021/enfuem|doi-broken-date=2020-03-22}}</ref>\n* Editorial Advisory Board Member: [[Fluid Phase Equilibria]] (Elsevier)<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.journals.elsevier.com/fluid-phase-equilibria/editorial-board/p-linga|title=P. Linga|website=www.journals.elsevier.com}}</ref>\n\n==Research areas==\n\nLinga's research interests are in the areas of [[clathrate hydrate]] or gas hydrate, energy storage, carbon dioxide capture and storage (CCS) and energy recovery. His targeted applications are seawater desalination, gas storage, data center cooling and carbon capture & storage. A part of his research is also focused on energy recovery from [[methane hydrate]], which is considered as a huge energy resource for natural gas.<ref>{{Cite journal|url=http://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/S030626191401318X|title=Review of natural gas hydrates as an energy resource: Prospects and challenges|first1=Zheng Rong|last1=Chong|first2=She Hern Bryan|last2=Yang|first3=Ponnivalavan|last3=Babu|first4=Praveen|last4=Linga|first5=Xiao-Sen|last5=Li|date=January 15, 2016|journal=Applied Energy|volume=162|pages=1633\u20131652|via=ScienceDirect|doi=10.1016/j.apenergy.2014.12.061}}</ref>\n\nHis research group has been working on process innovation and process development to scale-up [[clathrate hydrate]] as a technology enabler for clean energy and sustainable applications.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/eco-friendly-ways-to-harness-natural-gas-efficiently|title=Eco-friendly ways to harness natural gas efficiently|date=June 30, 2017|website=The Straits Times}}</ref> These applications include seawater desalination<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.engineersaustralia.org.au/News/drinkable-water-cold-energy|title=Drinkable water from cold energy &#124; Engineers Australia|website=www.engineersaustralia.org.au}}</ref>, solidified natural gas (SNG) technology for gas storage<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/vision-to-make-electric-cars-popular-by-2050|title=Vision to make electric cars popular by 2050|date=June 4, 2016|website=The Straits Times}}</ref>, development of a new cooling technology for data centre with [[clathrate hydrates]] as a medium.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://news.nus.edu.sg/press-releases/new-cooling-technology-for-data-centres|title=NUS, Keppel and SLNG join forces to develop new energy-efficient cooling technology for data centres|website=NUS News}}</ref>.\n\n==Honours and awards==\n\nIn 2018, [[Clarivate Analytics]] named him as one of the World's Most Influential Scientific Minds<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://news.nus.edu.sg/press-releases/highly-cited-researchers-2018|title=30 NUS researchers among the world's most highly cited researchers|website=NUS News|language=en|access-date=2020-03-10}}</ref> and Highly Cited Researchers in Engineering.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://apsc.ubc.ca/news/2019/01/apsc-alumni-included-global-list-of-highly-cited-researchers|title=APSC alumni included in global list of highly cited researchers &#124; UBC Applied Science|website=apsc.ubc.ca}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://gashydrates.chbe.nus.edu.sg/Achievements/2018_11_27_Highly%20Cited%20Researcher%20Award.tiff |title=Award lsit |publisher=gashydrates.chbe.nus.edu.sg |date=2018 |accessdate=2020-02-14}}</ref> He is one of the recipients of the SCEJ Award for Outstanding Asian Researcher and Engineer in 2020.<ref>http://www.scej.org/docs/en/awards/scej-award-for-oare/winner.pdf</ref> This prestigious award is given annually to individuals who have accomplished outstanding achievements in chemical engineering in Asia by the Society of Chemical Engineers, Japan (SCEJ).<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.scej.org/en/awards/scej-award-for-oare.html|title=The SCEJ Award for Outstanding Asian Researcher and Engineer}}</ref> In 2017, he was awarded the Donald W. Davidson Award at the 9th International Conference on Gas Hydrates (ICGH9) held in Denver USA for his outstanding contributions to gas hydrate research.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://gashydrates.chbe.nus.edu.sg/Achievements/2017_06_28-Don%20Davidson%20Award%20ICGH%20Conference.jpeg |title=Award list |publisher=gashydrates.chbe.nus.edu.sg |date=2017 |accessdate=2020-02-14}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.eng.nus.edu.sg/news/nus-engineering-researchers-win-two-top-awards-at-the-9th-international-conference-on-gas-hydrates/ |title=Researchers win two awards |publisher=www.eng.nus.edu.sg |date= |accessdate=2020-02-14}}</ref> He was awarded the prestigious Young Researcher Award (YRA) in NUS in 2017.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nus.edu.sg/uawards/2017/praveen_linga.php |title=National University of Singapore - University Awards 2017 |publisher=NUS |date= |accessdate=2020-02-14}}</ref> He is an elected fellow of the Royal Society of Chemistry in United Kingdom.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.eng.nus.edu.sg/news/dr-praveen-linga-elected-fellow-of-royal-society-of-chemistry/ |title=Info |publisher=www.eng.nus.edu.sg |date= |accessdate=2020-02-14}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://gashydrates.chbe.nus.edu.sg/Achievements/2019_06_FRSC%20Certificate.png |title=Achievements |publisher=gashydrates.chbe.nus.edu.sg |date=2019 |accessdate=2020-02-14}}</ref>\n\nFor his teaching, he received the Annual Teaching Excellence Award (ATEA) in 2017 from [[National University of Singapore]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://nus.edu.sg/cdtl/teaching-and-learning-quality/teaching-awards/teaching-award-winners/past-annual-teaching-excellence-award-(atea)-winners|title=Past Annual Teaching Excellence Award (ATEA) Winners|website=nus.edu.sg}}</ref> ATEA is awarded to faculty members who have displayed a high level of commitment to their teaching for the year under review.\n\n==Selected publications==\nLinga has published more than 100 peer-reviewed journal articles with an h index of 46.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://scholar.google.com.sg/citations?hl=en&user=6NpSa1kAAAAJ&view_op=list_works&sortby=pubdate|title=Praveen Linga PhD, PEng, FRSC - Google Scholar Citations|website=scholar.google.com.sg|access-date=2020-02-27}}</ref> A selected list of the review papers published by his group are listed below.\n* He, T.; Chong, Z. R.; Zheng, J.; Ju, Y.; Linga, P. LNG Cold Energy Utilization: Prospects and Challenges. Energy 2019, 170, 557\u2013568. doi:[http://doi.org/10.1016/j.energy.2018.12.170 10.1016/j.energy.2018.12.170]\n* Babu, P.; Nambiar, A.; He, T.; Karimi, I.A.; Lee, J. D.; Englezos, P.; Linga, P. A review of clathrate hydrate based desalination to strengthen energy-water nexus. ACS Sustainable Chemistry & Engineering 2018, 6 (7), 8093\u20138107. doi:[http://doi.org/10.1021/acssuschemeng.8b01616 10.1021/acssuschemeng.8b01616]\n* Veluswamy, H. P.; Kumar, A.; Seo, Y.; Lee, J. D.; Linga, P. A review of solidified natural gas (SNG) technology for gas storage via clathrate hydrates. Applied Energy (2018), 216, 262\u2013285. doi:[http://doi.org/10.1016/j.apenergy.2018.02.059 10.1016/j.apenergy.2018.02.059]\n* Yin, Z.; Khurana, M.; Tan, H.K.; Linga, P. A review of gas hydrate growth kinetic models Chemical Engineering Journal (2018), 342, 9-29. doi:[http://doi.org/10.1016/j.cej.2018.01.120 10.1016/j.cej.2018.01.120]\n* Khurana, M.; Yin, Z.; Linga, P. A review of clathrate hydrate nucleation ACS Sustainable Chemistry and Engineering (2017), 5 (12), 11176\u201311203. doi:[http://doi.org/10.1021/acssuschemeng.7b03238 10.1021/acssuschemeng.7b03238]\n* Yin, Z.; Chong, Z. R.; Tan, H. K.; Linga, P. Review of gas hydrate dissociation kinetic models for energy recovery. Journal of Natural Gas Science and Engineering (2016), 35, 1362\u20131387. doi:[http://doi.org/10.1016/j.jngse.2016.04.050 10.1016/j.jngse.2016.04.050]\n* Chong, Z. R.; Yang, S. H. B.; Babu, P.; Linga, P.; Li, X.-S. Review of natural gas hydrates as an energy resource: Prospects and Challenges. Applied Energy (2016), 162, 1633\u20131652. doi:[http://doi.org/10.1016/j.apenergy.2014.12.061 10.1016/j.apenergy.2014.12.061]\n* Babu, P.; Linga, P.; Kumar, R.*; Englezos, P. A review of the hydrate based gas separation (HBGS) process for carbon dioxide pre-combustion capture. Energy (2015), 85, 261\u2013279. doi:[http://doi.org/10.1016/j.energy.2015.03.103 10.1016/j.energy.2015.03.103]\n* Veluswamy, H. P.; Kumar, R.; Linga, P. Hydrogen storage in clathrate hydrates: Current state of the art and future directions. Applied Energy (2014), 122, 112\u2013132. doi:[http://doi.org/10.1016/j.apenergy.2014.01.063 10.1016/j.apenergy.2014.01.063]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n* {{cite web|url=http://orcid.org/0000-0002-1466-038X\n|title=Praveen Linga's ORCiD profile\n|date=\n|publisher=ORCiD\n|accessdate=}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [http://gashydrates.chbe.nus.edu.sg/ Linga lab]\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Linga, Praveen}}\n[[Category:Na