d natural gas (SNG) technology via [[clathrate hydrates]] for natural gas storage and transport.\n\n==Educational background==\nLinga was born on April 21, 1979 in Chennai, India. His father was an agriculturist. During his primary years of education, up to 3rd standard, he went to [[St. Mary's Home Matriculation School]] in Kothagiri, Tamil Nadu, India. From 6th to 12th standard, he studied at Infant Jesus Matriculation Higher Secondary School in Manali New Town, Chennai, India. He obtained his Bachelor of Technology degree in Chemical Engineering from Sri Ram Engineering College affiliated to the [[University of Madras]] in 2000. He then went on to pursue his Master of Technology degree at [[Indian Institute of Technology Kharagpur]] and graduated in 2002.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://kgpchronicle.iitkgp.ac.in/frsc-for-kgpian-praveen-linga/|title=FRSC for Kgpian Praveen Linga \u2013 The KGP Chronicle}}</ref> In 2004, he joined the Department of Chemical and Biological Engineering at [[The University of British Columbia]] to pursue his doctoral studies. Under the supervision of Professor Peter Englezos, he obtained his doctoral degree in 2009.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.grad.ubc.ca/prospective-students/graduate-student-research/convocation-may-2009|title=Convocation May 2009|website=UBC Graduate and Postdoctoral Studies}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://academictree.org/etree/tree.php?pid=100963|title=E-Tree - Praveen Linga Family Tree|website=academictree.org}}</ref> He did his Postdoctoral fellowship in the Department of Chemical and Biological Engineering at [[The University of British Columbia]] for a year (2009-2010). He was the first in his family's lineage to pursue post graduation in education.\n\n==Career==\n\nIn 2010, he started his academic career at the National University of Singapore (NUS) as an Assistant Professor in the Department of Chemical and Biomolecular Engineering specializing in gas hydrates technology. In 2016, he was appointed as an Associate Professor with tenure and in 2019, he was appointed as the Dean's Chair Associate Professor.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.eng.nus.edu.sg/chbe/staff/chepl/ |title=Staff |publisher=www.eng.nus.edu.sg |date= |accessdate=2020-02-14}}</ref>\nHe is also a visiting professor of Guangzhou Institute of Energy Conversion<ref>{{cite web|url=http://gashydrates.chbe.nus.edu.sg/Achievements/2018-2022_GIEC-CAS%20Institute%20Approval.jpeg |title=Instsute approval |publisher=gashydrates.chbe.nus.edu.sg |date=2018 |accessdate=2020-02-14}}</ref> Chinese Academy of Sciences, Guangzhou, [[PR China]] and a visiting guest professor of [[Harbin Engineering University]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://gashydrates.chbe.nus.edu.sg/Achievements/Harbin%20Engineering%20University_Visiting%20Professor%20Appointment.jpeg |title=Visiting professors |publisher=gashydrates.chbe.nus.edu.sg |date= |accessdate=2020-02-14}}</ref> [[PR China]].\n\nHe is a licensed Professional Engineer (P.Eng.) in Singapore. He also serves as a scientific editor in various engineering journals \n* Subject Editor: [[Applied Energy]] (Elsevier)<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.journals.elsevier.com/applied-energy/editorial-board|title=Applied Energy Editorial Board|via=www.journals.elsevier.com}}</ref>\n* Associate Editor: Journal of Natural Gas Science and Engineering (Elsevier)<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.journals.elsevier.com/journal-of-natural-gas-science-and-engineering/editorial-board|title=Journal of Natural Gas Science and Engineering Editorial Board|via=www.journals.elsevier.com}}</ref>\n* Editorial Advisory Board Member: [[Energy & Fuels]] (ACS Publisher)<ref>{{cite journal|url=https://pubs.acs.org/journal/enfuem|title=Energy & Fuels|website=pubs.acs.org|doi=10.1021/enfuem|doi-broken-date=2020-03-22}}</ref>\n* Editorial Advisory Board Member: [[Fluid Phase Equilibria]] (Elsevier)<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.journals.elsevier.com/fluid-phase-equilibria/editorial-board/p-linga|title=P. Linga|website=www.journals.elsevier.com}}</ref>\n\n==Research areas==\n\nLinga's research interests are in the areas of [[clathrate hydrate]] or gas hydrate, energy storage, carbon dioxide capture and storage (CCS) and energy recovery. His targeted applications are seawater desalination, gas storage, data center cooling and carbon capture & storage. A part of his research is also focused on energy recovery from [[methane hydrate]], which is considered as a huge energy resource for natural gas.<ref>{{Cite journal|url=http://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/S030626191401318X|title=Review of natural gas hydrates as an energy resource: Prospects and challenges|first1=Zheng Rong|last1=Chong|first2=She Hern Bryan|last2=Yang|first3=Ponnivalavan|last3=Babu|first4=Praveen|last4=Linga|first5=Xiao-Sen|last5=Li|date=January 15, 2016|journal=Applied Energy|volume=162|pages=1633\u20131652|via=ScienceDirect|doi=10.1016/j.apenergy.2014.12.061}}</ref>\n\nHis research group has been working on process innovation and process development to scale-up [[clathrate hydrate]] as a technology enabler for clean energy and sustainable applications.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/eco-friendly-ways-to-harness-natural-gas-efficiently|title=Eco-friendly ways to harness natural gas efficiently|date=June 30, 2017|website=The Straits Times}}</ref> These applications include seawater desalination<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.engineersaustralia.org.au/News/drinkable-water-cold-energy|title=Drinkable water from cold energy &#124; Engineers Australia|website=www.engineersaustralia.org.au}}</ref>, solidified natural gas (SNG) technology for gas storage<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/vision-to-make-electric-cars-popular-by-2050|title=Vision to make electric cars popular by 2050|date=June 4, 2016|website=The Straits Times}}</ref>, development of a new cooling technology for data centre with [[clathrate hydrates]] as a medium.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://news.nus.edu.sg/press-releases/new-cooling-technology-for-data-centres|title=NUS, Keppel and SLNG join forces to develop new energy-efficient cooling technology for data centres|website=NUS News}}</ref>.\n\n==Honours and awards==\n\nIn 2018, [[Clarivate Analytics]] named him as one of the World's Most Influential Scientific Minds<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://news.nus.edu.sg/press-releases/highly-cited-researchers-2018|title=30 NUS researchers among the world's most highly cited researchers|website=NUS News|language=en|access-date=2020-03-10}}</ref> and Highly Cited Researchers in Engineering.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://apsc.ubc.ca/news/2019/01/apsc-alumni-included-global-list-of-highly-cited-researchers|title=APSC alumni included in global list of highly cited researchers &#124; UBC Applied Science|website=apsc.ubc.ca}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://gashydrates.chbe.nus.edu.sg/Achievements/2018_11_27_Highly%20Cited%20Researcher%20Award.tiff |title=Award lsit |publisher=gashydrates.chbe.nus.edu.sg |date=2018 |accessdate=2020-02-14}}</ref> He is one of the recipients of the SCEJ Award for Outstanding Asian Researcher and Engineer in 2020.<ref>http://www.scej.org/docs/en/awards/scej-award-for-oare/winner.pdf</ref> This prestigious award is given annually to individuals who have accomplished outstanding achievements in chemical engineering in Asia by the Society of Chemical Engineers, Japan (SCEJ).<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.scej.org/en/awards/scej-award-for-oare.html|title=The SCEJ Award for Outstanding Asian Researcher and Engineer}}</ref> In 2017, he was awarded the Donald W. Davidson Award at the 9th International Conference on Gas Hydrates (ICGH9) held in Denver USA for his outstanding contributions to gas hydrate research.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://gashydrates.chbe.nus.edu.sg/Achievements/2017_06_28-Don%20Davidson%20Award%20ICGH%20Conference.jpeg |title=Award list |publisher=gashydrates.chbe.nus.edu.sg |date=2017 |accessdate=2020-02-14}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.eng.nus.edu.sg/news/nus-engineering-researchers-win-two-top-awards-at-the-9th-international-conference-on-gas-hydrates/ |title=Researchers win two awards |publisher=www.eng.nus.edu.sg |date= |accessdate=2020-02-14}}</ref> He was awarded the prestigious Young Researcher Award (YRA) in NUS in 2017.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nus.edu.sg/uawards/2017/praveen_linga.php |title=National University of Singapore - University Awards 2017 |publisher=NUS |date= |accessdate=2020-02-14}}</ref> He is an elected fellow of the Royal Society of Chemistry in United Kingdom.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.eng.nus.edu.sg/news/dr-praveen-linga-elected-fellow-of-royal-society-of-chemistry/ |title=Info |publisher=www.eng.nus.edu.sg |date= |accessdate=2020-02-14}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://gashydrates.chbe.nus.edu.sg/Achievements/2019_06_FRSC%20Certificate.png |title=Achievements |publisher=gashydrates.chbe.nus.edu.sg |date=2019 |accessdate=2020-02-14}}</ref>\n\nFor his teaching, he received the Annual Teaching Excellence Award (ATEA) in 2017 from [[National University of Singapore]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://nus.edu.sg/cdtl/teaching-and-learning-quality/teaching-awards/teaching-award-winners/past-annual-teaching-excellence-award-(atea)-winners|title=Past Annual Teaching Excellence Award (ATEA) Winners|website=nus.edu.sg}}</ref> ATEA is awarded to faculty members who have displayed a high level of commitment to their teaching for the year under review.\n\n==Selected publications==\nLinga has published more than 100 peer-reviewed journal articles with an h index of 46.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://scholar.google.com.sg/citations?hl=en&user=6NpSa1kAAAAJ&view_op=list_works&sortby=pubdate|title=Praveen Linga PhD, PEng, FRSC - Google Scholar Citations|website=scholar.google.com.sg|access-date=2020-02-27}}</ref> A selected list of the review papers published by his group are listed below.\n* He, T.; Chong, Z. R.; Zheng, J.; Ju, Y.; Linga, P. LNG Cold Energy Utilization: Prospects and Challenges. Energy 2019, 170, 557\u2013568. doi:[http://doi.org/10.1016/j.energy.2018.12.170 10.1016/j.energy.2018.12.170]\n* Babu, P.; Nambiar, A.; He, T.; Karimi, I.A.; Lee, J. D.; Englezos, P.; Linga, P. A review of clathrate hydrate based desalination to strengthen energy-water nexus. ACS Sustainable Chemistry & Engineering 2018, 6 (7), 8093\u20138107. doi:[http://doi.org/10.1021/acssuschemeng.8b01616 10.1021/acssuschemeng.8b01616]\n* Veluswamy, H. P.; Kumar, A.; Seo, Y.; Lee, J. D.; Linga, P. A review of solidified natural gas (SNG) technology for gas storage via clathrate hydrates. Applied Energy (2018), 216, 262\u2013285. doi:[http://doi.org/10.1016/j.apenergy.2018.02.059 10.1016/j.apenergy.2018.02.059]\n* Yin, Z.; Khurana, M.; Tan, H.K.; Linga, P. A review of gas hydrate growth kinetic models Chemical Engineering Journal (2018), 342, 9-29. doi:[http://doi.org/10.1016/j.cej.2018.01.120 10.1016/j.cej.2018.01.120]\n* Khurana, M.; Yin, Z.; Linga, P. A review of clathrate hydrate nucleation ACS Sustainable Chemistry and Engineering (2017), 5 (12), 11176\u201311203. doi:[http://doi.org/10.1021/acssuschemeng.7b03238 10.1021/acssuschemeng.7b03238]\n* Yin, Z.; Chong, Z. R.; Tan, H. K.; Linga, P. Review of gas hydrate dissociation kinetic models for energy recovery. Journal of Natural Gas Science and Engineering (2016), 35, 1362\u20131387. doi:[http://doi.org/10.1016/j.jngse.2016.04.050 10.1016/j.jngse.2016.04.050]\n* Chong, Z. R.; Yang, S. H. B.; Babu, P.; Linga, P.; Li, X.-S. Review of natural gas hydrates as an energy resource: Prospects and Challenges. Applied Energy (2016), 162, 1633\u20131652. doi:[http://doi.org/10.1016/j.apenergy.2014.12.061 10.1016/j.apenergy.2014.12.061]\n* Babu, P.; Linga, P.; Kumar, R.*; Englezos, P. A review of the hydrate based gas separation (HBGS) process for carbon dioxide pre-combustion capture. Energy (2015), 85, 261\u2013279. doi:[http://doi.org/10.1016/j.energy.2015.03.103 10.1016/j.energy.2015.03.103]\n* Veluswamy, H. P.; Kumar, R.; Linga, P. Hydrogen storage in clathrate hydrates: Current state of the art and future directions. Applied Energy (2014), 122, 112\u2013132. doi:[http://doi.org/10.1016/j.apenergy.2014.01.063 10.1016/j.apenergy.2014.01.063]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n* {{cite web|url=http://orcid.org/0000-0002-1466-038X\n|title=Praveen Linga's ORCiD profile\n|date=\n|publisher=ORCiD\n|accessdate=}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [http://gashydrates.chbe.nus.edu.sg/ Linga lab]\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Linga, Praveen}}\n[[Category:National University of Singapore faculty]]\n[[Category:1979 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Scientists from Chennai]]\n[[Category:University of British Columbia alumni]]\n[[Category:University of Madras alumni]]\n[[Category:Indian Institute of Technology Kharagpur alumni]]\n[[Category:University of the Chinese Academy of Sciences faculty]]\n[[Category:Harbin Engineering University faculty]]\n[[Category:Singaporean engineers]]\n[[Category:Indian chemical engineers]]\n[[Category:Fellows of the Royal Society of Chemistry]]\n", "name_user": "Sandpidu2", "label": "safe", "comment": "link error", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Praveen_Linga"}
{"title_page": "Marsh mongoose", "text_new": "{{speciesbox\n| name = Marsh mongoose\n| status = LC\n| status_system = IUCN3.1\n| status_ref = <ref name=iucn>{{cite iucn |title=''Atilax paludinosus'' |authors=Do Linh San, E., Angelici, F. M., Maddock, A. H., Baker, C. M. & Ray, J. |date=2015 |page=e.T41590A45204865}}</ref>\n| genus = Atilax\n| parent_authority = [[Fr\u00e9d\u00e9ric Cuvier|F. Cuvier]], 1826\n| species = paludinosus\n| authority = [[Georges Cuvier|G. Cuvier]], 1829\n| display_parents = 2\n| range_map =Atilax paludinosus range map.png\n| image = Marsh mongoose or water mongoose, Atilax paludinosus, at Rietvlei Nature Reserve, Gauteng, South Africa (22548192738).jpg\n}}\nThe '''marsh mongoose''' (''Atilax paludinosus'') is a medium-sized [[mongoose]] native to [[sub-Saharan Africa]], where it inhabits foremost [[freshwater]] [[wetland]]s. It has been listed as [[Least Concern]] on the [[IUCN Red List]] since 2008.<ref name=iucn/>\n\n== Taxonomy ==\nThe [[Generic name (biology)|generic name]] ''Atilax'' was introduced in 1826 by [[Fr\u00e9d\u00e9ric Cuvier]].<ref>{{cite book |authors=Cuvier, F. G. |year=1826 |chapter=Vansire |title=Histoire Naturelle des Mammif\u00e8res : avec des figures originales, colori\u00e9es, dessin\u00e9es d'apr\u00e8sdes animaux vivans. Tome 5 |editors=E. Geoffroy Saint-Hilaire and F. G. Cuvier |publisher=A. Belin |location=Paris |page=LIV |chapterurl=https://archive.org/details/HistoirenaturelVGeof/page/n223}}</ref>\nIn 1829, [[Georges Cuvier]] referred to a mongoose in the [[marsh]]es of the [[Cape Province]] using the [[scientific name]] ''Herpestes paludinosus''.<ref>{{cite book |author=Cuvier, G. |year=1829 |title=Le r\u00e8gne animal distribu\u00e9 d'apr\u00e8s son organisation, pour servir de base \u00e0 l'histoire naturelle des animaux et d'introduction \u00e0 l'anatomie compar\u00e9e |chapter=Les Mangoustes. Cuv. (Herpestes, Illiger) |publisher=Chez D\u00e9terville |location=Paris |pages=157\u2013158 |chapterurl=https://archive.org/details/lergneanimaldi01regn/page/158}}</ref>\nIt is the [[monotype|only member]] of the genus ''Atilax''.<ref name=msw3>{{MSW3 Wozencraft| id=14000479 |heading=''Atilax paludinosus'' |page=562}}</ref>\n\n==Characteristics==\nThe marsh mongoose's [[fur]] is dark reddish brown to black with white and fawn coloured [[guard hair]]s. The hair behind the neck and in front of the back is short, but longer on the hind legs and on the tail. Its muzzle is short with a fawn coloured mouth, short whiskers and a naked [[rhinarium]]. It has {{DentalFormula |upper=3.1.3.2 |lower=3.1.3.2 |total=36}} teeth. Its short ears are round. It has two [[nipples]].\u00a0Its feet have five flexible digits each with curved [[claw]]s, but without any webbing. The soles of its feet are naked.<ref name=Baker2013>{{cite book |author=Baker, C. M. and Ray, J. C. |year=2013 |title=The Mammals of Africa. V. Carnivores, Pangolins, Equids and Rhinoceroses |publisher=Bloomsbury |location=London |pages=298\u2212302 |chapter=Genus ''Atilax paludinosus'' Marsh Mongoose | editors=J. Kingdon and M. Hoffmann (eds.) |chapterurl=https://books.google.com/books?id=B_07noCPc4kC&lpg=PP1&pg=RA4-PA298#v=onepage&f=false |isbn=9781408189962}}</ref>\n\nFemales measure {{convert|48.72|cm|in|abbr=on}} in head-to-body length, and males {{convert|51.38|cm|in|abbr=on}}, with a {{convert|32.18|-|34.11|cm|in|abbr=on}} long tail. In weight, adults range from {{convert|2.56|to|2.95|kg|lb|abbr=on}}. Both sexes have anal [[gland]]s in a pouch that produce a musky smelling secretion.<ref>{{cite journal |author=Baker, C. M. |year=1992 |title=''Atilax paludinosus'' |journal=Mammalian Species |volume=408 |pages=1\u20136 |url=http://www.science.smith.edu/msi/pdf/i0076-3519-408-01-0001.pdf |access-date=22 September 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150924122147/http://www.science.smith.edu/msi/pdf/i0076-3519-408-01-0001.pdf |archive-date=24 September 2015 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\n==Distribution and habitat==\nThe marsh mongoose occurs in sub-Saharan Africa from [[Senegal]] to [[Ethiopia]], and south to [[Southern Africa]], except Namibia.<ref name=iucn/>\nIt inhabits freshwater wetlands such as [[marsh]]es and [[swamp]]s along slow-moving rivers and streams, but also [[Estuary|estuarie]]s in coastal areas.<ref name=Baker2013/>\nIt was probably introduced to [[Pemba Island]] in the [[Zanzibar Archipelago]].<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Walsh |first1=M. T. |year=2007 |title=Island subsistence: hunting, trapping and the translocation of wildlife in the Western Indian Ocean |journal=Azania: Journal of the British Institute in Eastern Africa |volume=42 |issue=1 |pages=83\u2212113 |doi=10.1080/00672700709480452 |url=https://www.academia.edu/download/3885083/Walsh_2007_Island_Subsistence_2007.pdf}}</ref>\n\nIn [[Guinea]]'s [[National Park of Upper Niger]], it was recorded during surveys conducted in 1996 to 1997.<ref>{{Cite journal |last=Ziegler |first=S. |last2=Nikolaus |first2=G. |last3=Hutterer |first3=R. |date=2002 |title=High mammalian diversity in the newly established National Park of Upper Niger, Republic of Guinea |journal=Oryx |volume=36 |issue=1 |pages=73\u201380 |doi= 10.1017/s003060530200011x|url=https://www.researchgate.net/profile/Rainer_Hutterer/publication/231894098_High_mammalian_diversity_in_the_newly_established_National_Park_of_Upper_Niger_Republic_of_Guinea/links/5722f6cb08ae586b21d401b8/High-mammalian-diversity-in-the-newly-established-National-Park-of-Upper-Niger-Republic-of-Guinea.pdf}}</ref>\nIn [[Gabon]]\u2019s [[Moukalaba-Doudou National Park]], it was recorded only in forested habitats during a two-months survey in 2012.<ref>{{cite journal |author=Nakashima, Y. |year=2015 |title=Inventorying medium-and large-sized mammals in the African lowland rainforest using camera trapping |journal=Tropics |volume=23 |issue=4 |pages=151\u2013164 |doi=10.3759/tropics.23.151}}</ref>\n\nIn the [[Ethiopian Highlands]], it was recorded at an altitude of {{convert|3950|m|ft|abbr=on}} in [[Bale Mountains National Park]].<ref>{{cite journal |authors=Yalden, D. W., Largen, M. J., Kock, D. and Hillman, J. C. |year=1996 |title=Catalogue of the Mammals of Ethiopia and Eritrea. Revised checklist, zoogeography and conservation |journal=Tropical Zoology 9 |issue=1 |pages=73\u2212164}}</ref>\n\n==Behaviour and ecology==\nThe marsh mongoose is [[wikt:solitary|solitary]].<ref name=Baker1989>{{cite journal |authors=Baker, C. M. |year=1989 |title=Feeding habits of the water mongoose (''Atilax paludinosus'') |journal=Zeitschrift f\u00fcr S\u00e4ugetierkunde |volume=54 |issue=1 |pages=31\u201339 |url=http://www.zobodat.at/pdf/Zeitschrift-Saeugetierkunde_54_0031-0039.pdf}}</ref>\nIt is an excellent swimmer and can dive for up to 15 seconds, using its feet to paddle. On land, it usually trots slowly, but can also move fast.<ref>{{cite journal |authors=Taylor, M. E. |year=1970 |title=Locomotion in some African viverrids |journal=Journal of Mammalogy |volume=51 |issue=1 |pages=42\u201351 |doi=10.2307/1378530}}</ref>\n[[Radio telemetry|Radio-collared]] marsh mongooses in [[Kwa-Zulu Natal]] showed [[crepuscular]] activity, and were active from shortly after sunset until after midnight, but not during the day.<ref>{{cite journal |authors=Maddock, A. H. and Perrin, M. R. |year=1993 |title=Spatial and temporal ecology of an assemblage of viverrids in Natal, South Africa |journal=Journal of Zoology |volume=229 |issue=2 |pages=277\u2013287 |doi=10.1111/j.1469-7998.1993.tb02636.x}}</ref>\nA male\u00a0marsh mongoose radio-collared in [[Dzanga-Sangha Special Reserve]] was most active in early mornings and late evenings. During the day it rested in burrows situated in dry areas above water and mud in dense cover of high grasses and [[climbing plants]].<ref>{{cite journal |author=Ray, J. |year=1997 |title=Comparative ecology of two African forest mongooses, ''Herpestes naso'' and ''Atilax paludinosus'' |journal=African Journal of Ecology |volume=35 |issue=3 |pages=237\u2013253 |doi=10.1111/j.1365-2028.1997.086-89086.x}}</ref>\n\n===Feeding behaviour and diet===\nFeeding behaviour of eight captive marsh mongooses was studied in 1984. When the mongooses sighted prey in the water, they swam or walked towards it, used their digits to seek it out, but kept their heads above water. Once located, they grabbed it with the mouth and killed it outside the water. They killed [[rodent]]s and [[frog]]s by biting them in the head, and occasionally also shook them. When finished eating, they wiped their mouths with the forefeet. They broke eggs by throwing them backwards between the legs.<ref name=Baker1989/>\nScat of marsh mongooses collected around [[Lake St Lucia]] contained foremost remains of [[crustacean]]s, [[amphibian]]s, [[insect]]s and [[fish]]. Marsh mongooses were observed while carrying [[mudcrab]]s (''Scylla serrata'') ashore. They removed the [[Chela (organ)|chelipeds]] and opened the [[sternum]] to feed on the body contents.<ref>{{cite journal |authors=Whitfield, A. K. and Blaber, S. J. M. |year=1980 |title=The diet of ''Atilax paludinosus'' (water mongoose) at St Lucia, South Africa |journal=Mammalia |volume=44 |issue=3 |pages=315\u2013318 |url=https://www.researchgate.net/profile/Alan_Whitfield/publication/249943246_The_diet_of_Atilax_paludinosus_water_mongoose_at_St_Lucia_South_Africa/links/5559bbb408ae6fd2d8271e6c/The-diet-of-Atilax-paludinosus-water-mongoose-at-St-Lucia-South-Africa.pdf |doi=10.1515/mamm.1980.44.3.315}}</ref>\nThey deposit scat at specific [[latrine]] sites located on low shrubs, on rocks or sand well away from the water edge. Scat of marsh mongoose collected in a rocky coastal habitat contained remains of [[sandhopper]]s, shore crab (''Cyclograpsus punctatus''), pink-lipped topshell (''[[Oxystele sinensis]]'') and ''[[Tropidophora]]'' snails.<ref>{{cite journal |authors=Louw, C. J., Nel, J. A. J. |year=1986 |title=Diets of coastal and inland-dwelling water mongoose |journal= |volume=16 |issue=4 |pages=153\u2013156 |url=https://journals.co.za/docserver/fulltext/wild/16/4/3599.pdf}}</ref>\nResearch in southeastern [[Nigeria]] revealed that the marsh mongoose has an [[omnivorous]] diet. It feeds on rodents like [[giant pouched rat]]s (''Cricetomys''), [[Temminck's mouse]] (''Mus musculoides''), [[Tullberg's soft-furred mouse]] (''Praomys tulbergi''), [[grass frog]]s (''Ptychadena''), [[crowned bullfrog]]\u00a0(''Hoplobatrachus occipitalis''), herald snake (''[[Crotaphopeltis hotamboeia]]''), [[mudskipper]]s (''Periophthalmus''), insects such as [[spider]]s and [[Coleoptera]], [[snails and slugs]], [[Bivalvia]], [[Decapoda]] as well as fruits, berries and seeds.<ref>{{cite journal |author=Angelici, F. M. |year=2000 |title=Food habits and resource partitioning of carnivores (Herpestidae, Viverridae) in the rainforests of southeastern Nigeria: preliminary results |journal=Revue\u00a0d'\u00c9cologie\u00a0(La\u00a0Terre\u00a0et La\u00a0Vie) |volume=55 |pages=67\u201376 |url=http://documents.irevues.inist.fr/bitstream/handle/2042/55398/RevuedEcologie_2000_55_1_67.pdf?sequence=1}}</ref>\n\n===Reproduction===\nAfter a [[gestation]] of 69 to 80 days, females give birth to a litter of two to three young, which are fully furred. Their eyes open between the 9th and 14th day, pupils are bluish at first and change to brown at the age of three weeks. Their [[ear canal]] opens between the 17th and 28th day. Females start [[weaning]] their offspring earliest on the 30th day, and young are fully weaned by the age of two months.<ref>{{cite journal |authors=Baker, C. M., Meester, J. |year=1986 |title=Postnatal physical development of the Water mongoose (Atilax paludinosus) |journal=Zeitschrift f\u00fcr S\u00e4ugetierkunde |volume=51 |issue=4 |pages=236\u2013243 |url=http://www.zobodat.at/pdf/Zeitschrift-Saeugetierkunde_51_0236-0243.pdf}}</ref>\n\n==Threats==\nIn 2006, it was estimated that about 950 marsh mongooses are hunted yearly in the Cameroon part of the [[Cross-Sanaga-Bioko coastal forests]].<ref>{{cite journal |authors=Fa, J. E., Seymour, S., Dupain, J. E. F., Amin, R., Albrechtsen, L. and Macdonald, D. |year=2006 |title=Getting to grips with the magnitude of exploitation: bushmeat in the Cross\u2013Sanaga rivers region, Nigeria and Cameroon |journal=Biological Conservation |volume=129 |issue=4 |pages=497\u2013510 |url=https://www.researchgate.net/profile/John_E_Fa/publication/223445717_Getting_to_grips_with_the_magnitude_of_exploitation_Bushmeat_in_the_Cross-Sanaga_Rivers_region_Nigeria_and_Cameroon/links/59e5ca83aca272390edffbf6/Getting-to-grips-with-the-magnitude-of-exploitation-Bushmeat-in-the-Cross-Sanaga-Rivers-region-Nigeria-and-Cameroon.pdf |doi=10.1016/j.biocon.2005.11.031}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Wikispecies|Atilax paludinosus}}\n{{Commons category|Atilax paludinosus}}\n*[http://www.wildherps.com/travels/Africa2000/images/marsh_mongoose_big.jpg Picture of a Marsh mongoose]\n\n{{Carnivora|F.}}\n\n{{Taxonbar|from=Q855597}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:mongoose, marsh}}\n[[Category:Mongooses|marsh mongoose]]\n[[Category:Mammals of Sub-Saharan Africa]]\n[[Category:Mammals of Cameroon]]\n[[Category:Mammals of the Democratic Republic of the Congo]]\n[[Category:Mammals of Ethiopia]]\n[[Category:Mammals of Gabon]]\n[[Category:Mammals described in 1829|marsh mongoose]]\n[[Category:Taxa named by Georges Cuvier|marsh mongoose]]\n", "text_old": "{{speciesbox\n| name = Marsh mongoose\n| status = LC\n| status_system = IUCN3.1\n| status_ref = <ref name=iucn>{{cite iucn |title=''Atilax paludinosus'' |authors=Do Linh San, E., Angelici, F. M., Maddock, A. H., Baker, C. M. & Ray, J. |date=2015 |page=e.T41590A45204865}}</ref>\n| genus = Atilax\n| parent_authority = [[Fr\u00e9d\u00e9ric Cuvier|F. Cuvier]], 1826\n| species = paludinosus\n| authority = [[Georges Cuvier|Cuvier]], 1829\n| display_parents = 2\n| range_map =Atilax paludinosus range map.png\n| image = Marsh mongoose or water mongoose, Atilax paludinosus, at Rietvlei Nature Reserve, Gauteng, South Africa (22548192738).jpg\n}}\nThe '''marsh mongoose''' (''Atilax paludinosus'') is a medium-sized [[mongoose]] native to [[sub-Saharan Africa]], where it inhabits foremost [[freshwater]] [[wetland]]s. It has been listed as [[Least Concern]] on the [[IUCN Red List]] since 2008.<ref name=iucn/>\n\n== Taxonomy ==\nThe [[Generic name (biology)|generic name]] ''Atilax'' was introduced in 1826 by [[Fr\u00e9d\u00e9ric Cuvier]].<ref>{{cite book |authors=Cuvier, F. G. |year=1826 |chapter=Vansire |title=Histoire Naturelle des Mammif\u00e8res : avec des figures originales, colori\u00e9es, dessin\u00e9es d'apr\u00e8sdes animaux vivans. Tome 5 |editors=E. Geoffroy Saint-Hilaire and F. G. Cuvier |publisher=A. Belin |location=Paris |page=LIV |chapterurl=https://archive.org/details/HistoirenaturelVGeof/page/n223}}</ref>\nIn 1829, [[Georges Cuvier]] referred to a mongoose in the [[marsh]]es of the [[Cape Province]] using the [[scientific name]] ''Herpestes paludinosus''.<ref>{{cite book |author=Cuvier, G. |year=1829 |title=Le r\u00e8gne animal distribu\u00e9 d'apr\u00e8s son organisation, pour servir de base \u00e0 l'histoire naturelle des animaux et d'introduction \u00e0 l'anatomie compar\u00e9e |chapter=Les Mangoustes. Cuv. (Herpestes, Illiger) |publisher=Chez D\u00e9terville |location=Paris |pages=157\u2013158 |chapterurl=https://archive.org/details/lergneanimaldi01regn/page/158}}</ref>\nIt is the [[monotype|only member]] of the genus ''Atilax''.<ref name=msw3>{{MSW3 Wozencraft| id=14000479 |heading=''Atilax paludinosus'' |page=562}}</ref>\n\n==Characteristics==\nThe marsh mongoose's [[fur]] is dark reddish brown to black with white and fawn coloured [[guard hair]]s. The hair behind the neck and in front of the back is short, but longer on the hind legs and on the tail. Its muzzle is short with a fawn coloured mouth, short whiskers and a naked [[rhinarium]]. It has {{DentalFormula |upper=3.1.3.2 |lower=3.1.3.2 |total=36}} teeth. Its short ears are round. It has two [[nipples]].\u00a0Its feet have five flexible digits each with curved [[claw]]s, but without any webbing. The soles of its feet are naked.<ref name=Baker2013>{{cite book |author=Baker, C. M. and Ray, J. C. |year=2013 |title=The Mammals of Africa. V. Carnivores, Pangolins, Equids and Rhinoceroses |publisher=Bloomsbury |location=London |pages=298\u2212302 |chapter=Genus ''Atilax paludinosus'' Marsh Mongoose | editors=J. Kingdon and M. Hoffmann (eds.) |chapterurl=https://books.google.com/books?id=B_07noCPc4kC&lpg=PP1&pg=RA4-PA298#v=onepage&f=false |isbn=9781408189962}}</ref>\n\nFemales measure {{convert|48.72|cm|in|abbr=on}} in head-to-body length, and males {{convert|51.38|cm|in|abbr=on}}, with a {{convert|32.18|-|34.11|cm|in|abbr=on}} long tail. In weight, adults range from {{convert|2.56|to|2.95|kg|lb|abbr=on}}. Both sexes have anal [[gland]]s in a pouch that produce a musky smelling secretion.<ref>{{cite journal |author=Baker, C. M. |year=1992 |title=''Atilax paludinosus'' |journal=Mammalian Species |volume=408 |pages=1\u20136 |url=http://www.science.smith.edu/msi/pdf/i0076-3519-408-01-0001.pdf |access-date=22 September 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150924122147/http://www.science.smith.edu/msi/pdf/i0076-3519-408-01-0001.pdf |archive-date=24 September 2015 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\n==Distribution and habitat==\nThe marsh mongoose occurs in sub-Saharan Africa from [[Senegal]] to [[Ethiopia]], and south to [[Southern Africa]], except Namibia.<ref name=iucn/>\nIt inhabits freshwater wetlands such as [[marsh]]es and [[swamp]]s along slow-moving rivers and streams, but also [[Estuary|estuarie]]s in coastal areas.<ref name=Baker2013/>\nIt was probably introduced to [[Pemba Island]] in the [[Zanzibar Archipelago]].<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Walsh |first1=M. T. |year=2007 |title=Island subsistence: hunting, trapping and the translocation of wildlife in the Western Indian Ocean |journal=Azania: Journal of the British Institute in Eastern Africa |volume=42 |issue=1 |pages=83\u2212113 |doi=10.1080/00672700709480452 |url=https://www.academia.edu/download/3885083/Walsh_2007_Island_Subsistence_2007.pdf}}</ref>\n\nIn [[Guinea]]'s [[National Park of Upper Niger]], it was recorded during surveys conducted in 1996 to 1997.<ref>{{Cite journal |last=Ziegler |first=S. |last2=Nikolaus |first2=G. |last3=Hutterer |first3=R. |date=2002 |title=High mammalian diversity in the newly established National Park of Upper Niger, Republic of Guinea |journal=Oryx |volume=36 |issue=1 |pages=73\u201380 |doi= 10.1017/s003060530200011x|url=https://www.researchgate.net/profile/Rainer_Hutterer/publication/231894098_High_mammalian_diversity_in_the_newly_established_National_Park_of_Upper_Niger_Republic_of_Guinea/links/5722f6cb08ae586b21d401b8/High-mammalian-diversity-in-the-newly-established-National-Park-of-Upper-Niger-Republic-of-Guinea.pdf}}</ref>\nIn [[Gabon]]\u2019s [[Moukalaba-Doudou National Park]], it was recorded only in forested habitats during a two-months survey in 2012.<ref>{{cite journal |author=Nakashima, Y. |year=2015 |title=Inventorying medium-and large-sized mammals in the African lowland rainforest using camera trapping |journal=Tropics |volume=23 |issue=4 |pages=151\u2013164 |doi=10.3759/tropics.23.151}}</ref>\n\nIn the [[Ethiopian Highlands]], it was recorded at an altitude of {{convert|3950|m|ft|abbr=on}} in [[Bale Mountains National Park]].<ref>{{cite journal |authors=Yalden, D. W., Largen, M. J., Kock, D. and Hillman, J. C. |year=1996 |title=Catalogue of the Mammals of Ethiopia and Eritrea. Revised checklist, zoogeography and conservation |journal=Tropical Zoology 9 |issue=1 |pages=73\u2212164}}</ref>\n\n==Behaviour and ecology==\nThe marsh mongoose is [[wikt:solitary|solitary]].<ref name=Baker1989>{{cite journal |authors=Baker, C. M. |year=1989 |title=Feeding habits of the water mongoose (''Atilax paludinosus'') |journal=Zeitschrift f\u00fcr S\u00e4ugetierkunde |volume=54 |issue=1 |pages=31\u201339 |url=http://www.zobodat.at/pdf/Zeitschrift-Saeugetierkunde_54_0031-0039.pdf}}</ref>\nIt is an excellent swimmer and can dive for up to 15 seconds, using its feet to paddle. On land, it usually trots slowly, but can also move fast.<ref>{{cite journal |authors=Taylor, M. E. |year=1970 |title=Locomotion in some African viverrids |journal=Journal of Mammalogy |volume=51 |issue=1 |pages=42\u201351 |doi=10.2307/1378530}}</ref>\n[[Radio telemetry|Radio-collared]] marsh mongooses in [[Kwa-Zulu Natal]] showed [[crepuscular]] activity, and were active from shortly after sunset until after midnight, but not during the day.<ref>{{cite journal |authors=Maddock, A. H. and Perrin, M. R. |year=1993 |title=Spatial and temporal ecology of an assemblage of viverrids in Natal, South Africa |journal=Journal of Zoology |volume=229 |issue=2 |pages=277\u2013287 |doi=10.1111/j.1469-7998.1993.tb02636.x}}</ref>\nA male\u00a0marsh mongoose radio-collared in [[Dzanga-Sangha Special Reserve]] was most active in early mornings and late evenings. During the day it rested in burrows situated in dry areas above water and mud in dense cover of high grasses and [[climbing plants]].<ref>{{cite journal |author=Ray, J. |year=1997 |title=Comparative ecology of two African forest mongooses, ''Herpestes naso'' and ''Atilax paludinosus'' |journal=African Journal of Ecology |volume=35 |issue=3 |pages=237\u2013253 |doi=10.1111/j.1365-2028.1997.086-89086.x}}</ref>\n\n===Feeding behaviour and diet===\nFeeding behaviour of eight captive marsh mongooses was studied in 1984. When the mongooses sighted prey in the water, they swam or walked towards it, used their digits to seek it out, but kept their heads above water. Once located, they grabbed it with the mouth and killed it outside the water. They killed [[rodent]]s and [[frog]]s by biting them in the head, and occasionally also shook them. When finished eating, they wiped their mouths with the forefeet. They broke eggs by throwing them backwards between the legs.<ref name=Baker1989/>\nScat of marsh mongooses collected around [[Lake St Lucia]] contained foremost remains of [[crustacean]]s, [[amphibian]]s, [[insect]]s and [[fish]]. Marsh mongooses were observed while carrying [[mudcrab]]s (''Scylla serrata'') ashore. They removed the [[Chela (organ)|chelipeds]] and opened the [[sternum]] to feed on the body contents.<ref>{{cite journal |authors=Whitfield, A. K. and Blaber, S. J. M. |year=1980 |title=The diet of ''Atilax paludinosus'' (water mongoose) at St Lucia, South Africa |journal=Mammalia |volume=44 |issue=3 |pages=315\u2013318 |url=https://www.researchgate.net/profile/Alan_Whitfield/publication/249943246_The_diet_of_Atilax_paludinosus_water_mongoose_at_St_Lucia_South_Africa/links/5559bbb408ae6fd2d8271e6c/The-diet-of-Atilax-paludinosus-water-mongoose-at-St-Lucia-South-Africa.pdf |doi=10.1515/mamm.1980.44.3.315}}</ref>\nThey deposit scat at specific [[latrine]] sites located on low shrubs, on rocks or sand well away from the water edge. Scat of marsh mongoose collected in a rocky coastal habitat contained remains of [[sandhopper]]s, shore crab (''Cyclograpsus punctatus''), pink-lipped topshell (''[[Oxystele sinensis]]'') and ''[[Tropidophora]]'' snails.<ref>{{cite journal |authors=Louw, C. J., Nel, J. A. J. |year=1986 |title=Diets of coastal and inland-dwelling water mongoose |journal= |volume=16 |issue=4 |pages=153\u2013156 |url=https://journals.co.za/docserver/fulltext/wild/16/4/3599.pdf}}</ref>\nResearch in southeastern [[Nigeria]] revealed that the marsh mongoose has an [[omnivorous]] diet. It feeds on rodents like [[giant pouched rat]]s (''Cricetomys''), [[Temminck's mouse]] (''Mus musculoides''), [[Tullberg's soft-furred mouse]] (''Praomys tulbergi''), [[grass frog]]s (''Ptychadena''), [[crowned bullfrog]]\u00a0(''Hoplobatrachus occipitalis''), herald snake (''[[Crotaphopeltis hotamboeia]]''), [[mudskipper]]s (''Periophthalmus''), insects such as [[spider]]s and [[Coleoptera]], [[snails and slugs]], [[Bivalvia]], [[Decapoda]] as well as fruits, berries and seeds.<ref>{{cite journal |author=Angelici, F. M. |year=2000 |title=Food habits and resource partitioning of carnivores (Herpestidae, Viverridae) in the rainforests of southeastern Nigeria: preliminary results |journal=Revue\u00a0d'\u00c9cologie\u00a0(La\u00a0Terre\u00a0et La\u00a0Vie) |volume=55 |pages=67\u201376 |url=http://documents.irevues.inist.fr/bitstream/handle/2042/55398/RevuedEcologie_2000_55_1_67.pdf?sequence=1}}</ref>\n\n===Reproduction===\nAfter a [[gestation]] of 69 to 80 days, females give birth to a litter of two to three young, which are fully furred. Their eyes open between the 9th and 14th day, pupils are bluish at first and change to brown at the age of three weeks. Their [[ear canal]] opens between the 17th and 28th day. Females start [[weaning]] their offspring earliest on the 30th day, and young are fully weaned by the age of two months.<ref>{{cite journal |authors=Baker, C. M., Meester, J. |year=1986 |title=Postnatal physical development of the Water mongoose (Atilax paludinosus) |journal=Zeitschrift f\u00fcr S\u00e4ugetierkunde |volume=51 |issue=4 |pages=236\u2013243 |url=http://www.zobodat.at/pdf/Zeitschrift-Saeugetierkunde_51_0236-0243.pdf}}</ref>\n\n==Threats==\nIn 2006, it was estimated that about 950 marsh mongooses are hunted yearly in the Cameroon part of the [[Cross-Sanaga-Bioko coastal forests]].<ref>{{cite journal |authors=Fa, J. E., Seymour, S., Dupain, J. E. F., Amin, R., Albrechtsen, L. and Macdonald, D. |year=2006 |title=Getting to grips with the magnitude of exploitation: bushmeat in the Cross\u2013Sanaga rivers region, Nigeria and Cameroon |journal=Biological Conservation |volume=129 |issue=4 |pages=497\u2013510 |url=https://www.researchgate.net/profile/John_E_Fa/publication/223445717_Getting_to_grips_with_the_magnitude_of_exploitation_Bushmeat_in_the_Cross-Sanaga_Rivers_region_Nigeria_and_Cameroon/links/59e5ca83aca272390edffbf6/Getting-to-grips-with-the-magnitude-of-exploitation-Bushmeat-in-the-Cross-Sanaga-Rivers-region-Nigeria-and-Cameroon.pdf |doi=10.1016/j.biocon.2005.11.031}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Wikispecies|Atilax paludinosus}}\n{{Commons category|Atilax paludinosus}}\n*[http://www.wildherps.com/travels/Africa2000/images/marsh_mongoose_big.jpg Picture of a Marsh mongoose]\n\n{{Carnivora|F.}}\n\n{{Taxonbar|from=Q855597}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:mongoose, marsh}}\n[[Category:Mongooses|marsh mongoose]]\n[[Category:Mammals of Sub-Saharan Africa]]\n[[Category:Mammals of Cameroon]]\n[[Category:Mammals of the Democratic Republic of the Congo]]\n[[Category:Mammals of Ethiopia]]\n[[Category:Mammals of Gabon]]\n[[Category:Mammals described in 1829|marsh mongoose]]\n[[Category:Taxa named by Georges Cuvier|marsh mongoose]]\n", "name_user": "Masquer11", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Marsh_mongoose"}
{"title_page": "East Meath", "text_new": "{{EngvarB|date=October 2013}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2013}}\n{{Infobox settlement\n| name                   = East Meath\n| native_name            = ''An Oirmh\u00ed''\n| settlement_type        = Area\n| image_skyline          = EastMeathMap.png\n| image_caption          = Location of East Meath (Red) within [[County Meath]]\n| image_shield           = \n| pushpin_map            = Ireland\n| pushpin_label_position = right\n| pushpin_map_caption    = Location in Ireland\n| coordinates            = \n| subdivision_type       = Country\n| subdivision_name       = [[Republic of Ireland|Ireland]]\n| subdivision_type1      = [[Provinces of Ireland|Province]]\n| subdivision_name1      = [[Leinster]]\n| subdivision_type2      = [[Counties of Ireland|County]]\n| subdivision_name2      = [[County Meath]]\n| subdivision_type3      = [[Municipal district (Ireland)|Municipal district]]\n| subdivision_name3      = Laytown-Bettystown\n| subdivision_type4      = D\u00e1il \u00c9ireann\n| subdivision_name4      = [[Louth (D\u00e1il constituency)|Louth]]\n| subdivision_type5      = EU Parliament\n| subdivision_name5      = [[Midlands\u2013North-West (European Parliament constituency)|Midlands\u2013North-West]]\n| established_title      = \n| established_date       = \n| elevation_max_m        = \n| elevation_min_m        = \n| population_footnotes   = \n| population_total       = 22,909\n| population_density_km2 = auto\n| area_total_km2          = 82\n| population_as_of       = Census 2016\n| timezone1              = [[Greenwich Mean Time|GMT]] ([[UTC\u00b100:00|UTC]])\n| utc_offset1            = +0\n| timezone1_DST          = [[Irish Standard Time|IST]] ([[Western European Summer Time|WEST]])\n| utc_offset1_DST        = -1\n| blank_name_sec2        = Dialing code\n| blank_info_sec2        = +353 41\n| website                = \n}}\n\n'''East Meath''' ({{lang-gle|An Oirmh\u00ed}}) is an area of made up of the electoral divisions of St Mary's (Part) and Julianstown in [[County Meath]]. The area is bound on the north by the [[River Boyne]] and [[County Louth]], to the south just beyond the River Nanny close to the [[County Dublin]] border, to the east by the [[Irish Sea]] and to the west by the [[M1 motorway (Republic of Ireland)|M1]]. It has been part of the [[Louth (D\u00e1il constituency)|D\u00e1il constituency of Louth]] since 2007.\n\n==Geography==\n[[File:Bettystown meath beach.jpg|thumb|right|Bettystown Beach]]\n\n===Urban areas===\n*[[Bettystown]]\n*[[Donacarney]]\n*Southern environs of [[Drogheda]]\n*[[Julianstown]]\n*[[Laytown]]\n*[[Mornington, County Meath|Mornington]]\n\n===Electoral divisions===\n*Julianstown\n*St. Mary's (Part)\n\n==Demographics==\nThe area is characterised by a series of densely populated urban areas which stretch across Meath's 12&nbsp;km coastline and mesh into one another. With a population of 22,909 according to the 2016 census, and an area of 82 km2, East Meath accounts for roughly 3.5% of the area and 11.7% of the population of County Meath. The largest centre of population is the [[List of census towns in the Republic of Ireland|census town]] of [[Laytown-Bettystown-Mornington]] which had a population of 11,872 recorded in 2016.\n\n==Defined area==\nThe Report on D\u00e1il and European Parliament Constituencies 2007 recommended ''\"that Louth should become a 5-seat constituency by extending the constituency southwards from, and in the environs of, Drogheda and taking in electoral divisions which have extensive linkages with the town. This will allow the inclusion of the town of Drogheda and hinterland areas in a single constituency.\"''<ref>http://www.constituency-commission.ie/docs%5Ccon2007.pdfThis{{dead link|date=September 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n\nThe [[Electoral (Amendment) Act 2009]] defines the constituency as:\n\"The county of [[County Louth|Louth]] and, in the county of [[County Meath|Meath]], the electoral divisions of Julianstown, St. Mary\u2019s (part), in the former ''Rural District of Meath''.\"<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.irishstatutebook.ie/pdf/2009/en.act.2009.0004.pdf |title=Electoral (Amendment) Act 2009|work=www.irishstatuebook.ie|access-date=17 July 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131022233318/http://www.irishstatutebook.ie/pdf/2009/en.act.2009.0004.pdf |archive-date=22 October 2013 |url-status=live |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\n==Sport==\n* St. Colmcille's GAA club serves the area of East Meath encompassing the villages of Laytown, Bettystown, Donacarney and Mornington. Their facilities are located at P\u00e1irc U\u00ed R\u00eds in Piltown, Bettystown.\n* Laytown and Bettystown Golf Club, Golflinks Road, Bettystown.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141229043528/http://www.landb.ie/Default.aspx|title=Laytown & Bettystown Golf Club |work=www.landb.ie|access-date=25 June 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141229043528/http://www.landb.ie/Default.aspx |archive-date=29 December 2014 |url-status=live |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n* Laytown and Bettystown Lawn Tennis Club, Golflinks Road, Bettystown.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.lbltc.ie/|title=Laytown & Bettystown Lawn Tennis Club|website=lbltc.ie|accessdate=16 February 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190125011539/https://www.lbltc.ie/|archive-date=25 January 2019|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n* East Meath United is a youths soccer football club that competes in the AUL, DDSL, DCSL and the NDSL. The football club, which was founded in 1999, plays its home matches at Minnistown Road, [[Laytown]], County Meath. The team's colours are claret, Blue and White.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://sites.google.com/site/eastmeathutd/home|title=Home - East Meath United FC|website=sites.google.com|accessdate=16 February 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160416151620/https://sites.google.com/site/eastmeathutd/home|archive-date=16 April 2016|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n==Transport==\n\n===Rail===\nLaytown Train Station serves the area with direct rail links to [[Dublin Connolly]].\n\n===Road===\nEast Meath can be reached via Exit 7 (Julianstown, Drogheda South), Exit 8 (Drogheda, Duleek) and Exit 9 (Drogheda Centre, Donore) on the [[M1 motorway (Republic of Ireland)|M1 motorway]] which connects Dublin to Belfast.\n\nEast Meath can be reached via the R132 (Previously N1) by joining the R150 north in Drogheda, or R150 south in Julainstown.\n\n===Bus===\n[[Bus \u00c9ireann]] 190/190A connects Laytown-Drogheda-(Via Slane)-Navan-Trim/Athboy.\n\nMatthews Coach Hire services East Meath with bus services to Dublin. The route serves, City North, [[Julianstown]], [[Laytown]], [[Bettystown]], [[Donacarney]] and [[Drogheda|Drogheda Colpe]].\n\n==Education==\n\n===Primary===\n* Donacarney Boys National School.\n* Gaelscoil an Bhradain Feasa, Drogheda.\n* Le Cheile [[Educate Together]] National School, Drogheda.\n* Re\u00e1lt Na Mara  Girls National School, Donacarney.\n* Scoil an Spiorad Naomh, Laytown.\n* Scoil Oilibh\u00e9ir Naofa, Laytown. \n* Whitecross National School, Julianstown.\n\n===Secondary===\n* [[Drogheda Grammar School]].\n\n==Churches==\n* Sacred Heart RC Church, Laytown.\n* Star of the Sea RC Church, Mornington.\n* St Mary's RC Church, Julianstown.\n* St Mary's Church of Ireland, Julianstown<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.meath.anglican.org.dnnmax.com/ParishesClergy/Julianstown/tabid/89/Default.aspx |title=Meath and Kildare|work=www.meath.anglican.org|accessdate=2014-06-25 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://archive.is/20140625190558/http://www.meath.anglican.org.dnnmax.com/ParishesClergy/Julianstown/tabid/89/Default.aspx |archivedate=25 June 2014 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n* Drogheda Presbyterian Church, Colpe East, Drogheda.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.droghedapresbyterian.ie/|title=Welcome to the Drogheda Presbyterian Church Website|website=www.droghedapresbyterian.ie|accessdate=16 February 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180808080940/http://droghedapresbyterian.ie/|archive-date=8 August 2018|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n==Ecology==\nSonairte is an interactive visitor centre established in 1986 which promotes ecological awareness and sustainable living. Sonairte, The Ninch, Laytown.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://sonairte.ie/|title=Sonairte|website=sonairte.ie|accessdate=16 February 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190111122439/http://sonairte.ie/|archive-date=11 January 2019|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n==Gallery==\n<gallery class=\"center\" >\nFile:Maiden Tower, Mornington, and Mouth of River Boyne - geograph.org.uk - 534835.jpg|Maiden Tower, Mornington\nFile:Laytown meath beach.jpg|Laytown viewed from across the river Nanny\nFile:Ship on River Boyne - geograph.org.uk - 571983.jpg|Ships on the Boyne at Mornington\nFile:Neptune Hotel, Bettystown.jpg|Neptune Hotel, Bettystown\nFile:Bettystown, Road Sign - geograph.org.uk - 312488.jpg|Bettystown road sign\nFile:Redundant lighthouse at Mornington, Co. Meath - geograph.org.uk - 545664.jpg|Mouth of the Boyne at Mornington\n</gallery>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20051227073753/http://planning.meath.ie/EastMeath_Lap/EM_LAP.pdf Official local area plans for East Meath (pdf)]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20140725163942/http://www.meath.ie/CountyCouncil/Publications/PlanningPublications/Laytown-BettystownPlanningPublications/Laytown-BettystownLocalAreaPlans2009-2015/File%2C36330%2Cen.pdf Local Area Plan for the Southern Environs of Drogheda 2009 - 2015]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20110812081706/http://www.droghedaboro.ie/droghedaboro/downloads/Drogheda%20Issues%20paper.pdf Planning Strategy for the Greater Drogheda Area]\n\n{{coord missing|County Meath}}\n\n[[Category:County Meath]]\n[[Category:Drogheda]]\n", "text_old": "{{EngvarB|date=October 2013}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2013}}\n{{Infobox settlement\n| name                 