9.0004.pdf |title=Electoral (Amendment) Act 2009|work=www.irishstatuebook.ie|access-date=17 July 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131022233318/http://www.irishstatutebook.ie/pdf/2009/en.act.2009.0004.pdf |archive-date=22 October 2013 |url-status=live |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\n==Sport==\n* St. Colmcille's GAA club serves the area of East Meath encompassing the villages of Laytown, Bettystown, Donacarney and Mornington. Their facilities are located at P\u00e1irc U\u00ed R\u00eds in Piltown, Bettystown.\n* Laytown and Bettystown Golf Club, Golflinks Road, Bettystown.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141229043528/http://www.landb.ie/Default.aspx|title=Laytown & Bettystown Golf Club |work=www.landb.ie|access-date=25 June 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141229043528/http://www.landb.ie/Default.aspx |archive-date=29 December 2014 |url-status=live |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n* Laytown and Bettystown Lawn Tennis Club, Golflinks Road, Bettystown.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.lbltc.ie/|title=Laytown & Bettystown Lawn Tennis Club|website=lbltc.ie|accessdate=16 February 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190125011539/https://www.lbltc.ie/|archive-date=25 January 2019|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n* East Meath United is a youths soccer football club that competes in the AUL, DDSL, DCSL and the NDSL. The football club, which was founded in 1999, plays its home matches at Minnistown Road, [[Laytown]], County Meath. The teams colours are claret, Blue and White.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://sites.google.com/site/eastmeathutd/home|title=Home - East Meath United FC|website=sites.google.com|accessdate=16 February 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160416151620/https://sites.google.com/site/eastmeathutd/home|archive-date=16 April 2016|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n==Transport==\n\n===Rail===\nLaytown Train Station serves the area with direct rail links to [[Dublin Connolly]].\n\n===Road===\nEast Meath can be reached via Exit 7 (Julianstown, Drogheda South), Exit 8 (Drogheda, Duleek) and Exit 9 (Drogheda Centre, Donore) on the [[M1 motorway (Republic of Ireland)|M1 motorway]] which connects Dublin to Belfast.\n\nEast Meath can be reached via the R132 (Previously N1) by joining the R150 north in Drogheda, or R150 south in Julainstown.\n\n===Bus===\n[[Bus \u00c9ireann]] 190/190A connects Laytown-Drogheda-(Via Slane)-Navan-Trim/Athboy.\n\nMatthews Coach Hire services East Meath with bus services to Dublin. The route serves, City North, [[Julianstown]], [[Laytown]], [[Bettystown]], [[Donacarney]] and [[Drogheda|Drogheda Colpe]].\n\n==Education==\n\n===Primary===\n* Donacarney Boys National School.\n* Gaelscoil an Bhradain Feasa, Drogheda.\n* Le Cheile [[Educate Together]] National School, Drogheda.\n* Re\u00e1lt Na Mara  Girls National School, Donacarney.\n* Scoil an Spiorad Naomh, Laytown.\n* Scoil Oilibh\u00e9ir Naofa, Laytown. \n* Whitecross National School, Julianstown.\n\n===Secondary===\n* [[Drogheda Grammar School]].\n\n==Churches==\n* Sacred Heart RC Church, Laytown.\n* Star of the Sea RC Church, Mornington.\n* St Mary's RC Church, Julianstown.\n* St Mary's Church of Ireland, Julianstown<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.meath.anglican.org.dnnmax.com/ParishesClergy/Julianstown/tabid/89/Default.aspx |title=Meath and Kildare|work=www.meath.anglican.org|accessdate=2014-06-25 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://archive.is/20140625190558/http://www.meath.anglican.org.dnnmax.com/ParishesClergy/Julianstown/tabid/89/Default.aspx |archivedate=25 June 2014 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n* Drogheda Presbyterian Church, Colpe East, Drogheda.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.droghedapresbyterian.ie/|title=Welcome to the Drogheda Presbyterian Church Website|website=www.droghedapresbyterian.ie|accessdate=16 February 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180808080940/http://droghedapresbyterian.ie/|archive-date=8 August 2018|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n==Ecology==\nSonairte is an interactive visitor centre established in 1986 which promotes ecological awareness and sustainable living. Sonairte, The Ninch, Laytown.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://sonairte.ie/|title=Sonairte|website=sonairte.ie|accessdate=16 February 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190111122439/http://sonairte.ie/|archive-date=11 January 2019|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n==Gallery==\n<gallery class=\"center\" >\nFile:Maiden Tower, Mornington, and Mouth of River Boyne - geograph.org.uk - 534835.jpg|Maiden Tower, Mornington\nFile:Laytown meath beach.jpg|Laytown viewed from across the river Nanny\nFile:Ship on River Boyne - geograph.org.uk - 571983.jpg|Ships on the Boyne at Mornington\nFile:Neptune Hotel, Bettystown.jpg|Neptune Hotel, Bettystown\nFile:Bettystown, Road Sign - geograph.org.uk - 312488.jpg|Bettystown road sign\nFile:Redundant lighthouse at Mornington, Co. Meath - geograph.org.uk - 545664.jpg|Mouth of the Boyne at Mornington\n</gallery>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20051227073753/http://planning.meath.ie/EastMeath_Lap/EM_LAP.pdf Official local area plans for East Meath (pdf)]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20140725163942/http://www.meath.ie/CountyCouncil/Publications/PlanningPublications/Laytown-BettystownPlanningPublications/Laytown-BettystownLocalAreaPlans2009-2015/File%2C36330%2Cen.pdf Local Area Plan for the Southern Environs of Drogheda 2009 - 2015]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20110812081706/http://www.droghedaboro.ie/droghedaboro/downloads/Drogheda%20Issues%20paper.pdf Planning Strategy for the Greater Drogheda Area]\n\n{{coord missing|County Meath}}\n\n[[Category:County Meath]]\n[[Category:Drogheda]]\n", "name_user": "John of Reading", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eSport:Typo fixing, replaced: teams colours \u2192 team's colours", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/East_Meath"}
